<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>BEEE Modules 1 & 2 — Study Dashboard v4</title>
<!-- Google Fonts -->
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@300;400;500;600;700&family=Sora:wght@400;600;700;800&family=Fira+Code:wght@400;500&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
<style>
/* Core CSS Design System */
:root {
  --bg-page: #0F0F0E;
  --bg-card: #181817;
  --bg-card-hover: #20201f;
  
  --text-primary: #F3F4F6;
  --text-secondary: #9CA3AF;
  --text-muted: #6B7280;
  
  /* Color Tokens */
  --accent-red: #EF4444; /* Tier 1 / Important Markers */
  --accent-red-bg: rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.12);
  --accent-red-border: rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.3);
  
  --accent-green: #22C55E; /* Answers / Definitions / Highlights */
  --accent-green-bg: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.08);
  --accent-green-border: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.25);
  
  --accent-blue: #3B82F6; /* Tier 2 / Info */
  --accent-blue-bg: rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.1);
  --accent-blue-border: rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.3);
  
  --accent-yellow: #F59E0B; /* Admonition Tips */
  --accent-yellow-bg: rgba(245, 158, 11, 0.08);
  --accent-yellow-border: rgba(245, 158, 11, 0.25);
  
  --border-color: #27272A;
  
  --font-sans: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  --font-display: 'Sora', sans-serif;
  --font-mono: 'Fira Code', monospace;
  
  --shadow-sm: 0 1px 2px 0 rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
  --shadow-md: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1), 0 2px 4px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.06);
  --shadow-lg: 0 10px 15px -3px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1), 0 4px 6px -2px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
}

* {
  box-sizing: border-box;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent;
}

body {
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  background-color: var(--bg-page);
  color: var(--text-primary);
  font-size: 15px;
  line-height: 1.7;
  padding-bottom: 60px;
}

/* Header & Top Bar styling */
.top-bar {
  background: rgba(15, 15, 14, 0.85);
  backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
  -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  padding: 14px 16px;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: 100;
}

.top-bar h1 {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 15px;
  font-weight: 700;
  letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 8px;
}

.top-bar .subtitle {
  font-size: 11px;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
}

/* Tab navigation with horizontal scroll and fade masks */
.tab-bar-container {
  position: sticky;
  top: 49px;
  z-index: 99;
  background: var(--bg-page);
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
}

.tab-bar {
  display: flex;
  overflow-x: auto;
  scrollbar-width: none; /* Hide scrollbar for Firefox */
  padding: 0 12px;
  gap: 4px;
}

.tab-bar::-webkit-scrollbar {
  display: none; /* Hide scrollbar for Chrome/Safari */
}

.tab {
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  padding: 12px 14px;
  font-size: 12px;
  font-weight: 600;
  border: none;
  background: none;
  cursor: pointer;
  color: var(--text-muted);
  border-bottom: 2px solid transparent;
  white-space: nowrap;
  transition: all 0.2s ease;
  margin-bottom: -1px;
}

.tab:hover:not(.active) {
  color: var(--text-primary);
}

.tab.active {
  color: var(--text-primary);
  border-bottom-color: var(--text-primary);
}

/* Priority based tab highlights */
.tab.t1.active {
  color: var(--accent-red);
  border-bottom-color: var(--accent-red);
}

.tab.t2.active {
  color: var(--accent-blue);
  border-bottom-color: var(--accent-blue);
}

.tab.t3.active {
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  border-bottom-color: var(--text-secondary);
}

/* Panel Layouts */
.panel {
  display: none;
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 16px 12px 60px;
  animation: fadeIn 0.25s ease-in-out;
}

.panel.active {
  display: block;
}

@keyframes fadeIn {
  from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(4px); }
  to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
}

/* Strategy & Dashboard Layout */
.priority-banner {
  background: linear-gradient(135deg, #450a0a, #7f1d1d);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-red-border);
  border-radius: 12px;
  padding: 18px;
  margin-bottom: 16px;
}

.priority-banner h2 {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 16px;
  font-weight: 700;
  margin-bottom: 6px;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 6px;
}

.priority-banner p {
  font-size: 12px;
  color: #fca5a5;
  line-height: 1.6;
}

.score-row {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  gap: 8px;
  margin-top: 14px;
}

@media(min-width: 480px) {
  .score-row {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
  }
}

.score-card {
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05);
  border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 10px;
  text-align: center;
}

.score-card .num {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 18px;
  font-weight: 800;
}

.score-card .lbl {
  font-size: 10px;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  margin-top: 2px;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
}

/* Priority Grids */
.p-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  gap: 12px;
  margin-bottom: 16px;
}

@media(min-width: 640px) {
  .p-grid {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
  }
}

.p-card {
  background: var(--bg-card);
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 12px;
  padding: 16px;
}

.p-card-1 {
  border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-red);
}

.p-card-2 {
  border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-blue);
}

.p-card-title {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 13px;
  font-weight: 700;
  margin-bottom: 12px;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 6px;
}

.p-item {
  font-size: 12px;
  padding: 8px 0;
  border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.04);
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 8px;
}

.p-item:last-child {
  border-bottom: none;
}

.p-item-name {
  color: var(--text-primary);
}

.p-count {
  font-size: 9px;
  font-weight: 700;
  padding: 2px 6px;
  border-radius: 4px;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  white-space: nowrap;
}

.c-red {
  background: var(--accent-red-bg);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-red-border);
  color: var(--accent-red);
}

.c-blue {
  background: var(--accent-blue-bg);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-blue-border);
  color: #60a5fa;
}

/* General Card/Topic structures */
.topic {
  background: var(--bg-card);
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 12px;
  margin-bottom: 16px;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.topic-header {
  padding: 14px 16px;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  gap: 8px;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
}

.topic-title {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 14px;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--text-primary);
}

.topic-body {
  padding: 16px;
}

/* Badges */
.badge {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 4px;
  font-size: 10px;
  font-weight: 700;
  padding: 3px 8px;
  border-radius: 4px;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  white-space: nowrap;
}

.badge-t1 {
  background: var(--accent-red-bg);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-red-border);
  color: var(--accent-red);
}

.badge-t2 {
  background: var(--accent-blue-bg);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-blue-border);
  color: #60a5fa;
}

.badge-t3 {
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05);
  border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
  color: var(--text-secondary);
}

/* Green Boxes (Answers and Key Definitions) */
.green-box, .qa-a {
  background: var(--accent-green-bg);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-green-border);
  border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-green);
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 14px;
  margin: 12px 0;
}

.green-box-title, .qa-a-title {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 11px;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--accent-green);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  margin-bottom: 6px;
}

/* Monospace formulas & items */
.f {
  font-family: var(--font-mono);
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.04);
  border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
  color: #34d399; /* soft green code in dark mode */
  padding: 2px 6px;
  border-radius: 4px;
  font-size: 13px;
  word-break: break-all;
}

.formula-box {
  background: rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.05);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-blue-border);
  border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-blue);
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 12px 14px;
  margin: 12px 0;
  font-family: var(--font-mono);
  font-size: 13px;
  color: #93c5fd;
}

.formula-box .flabel {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 10px;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: #60a5fa;
  margin-bottom: 6px;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  text-transform: uppercase;
}

.formula-box .formula-line {
  margin-bottom: 4px;
  display: block;
}

.formula-box .formula-line:last-child {
  margin-bottom: 0;
}

/* Diagrams */
.diag-box {
  border: 1px dashed var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 14px;
  margin: 12px 0;
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.01);
}

.must-diag {
  border-color: var(--accent-red-border);
  background: rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.02);
}

.diag-box .dlabel {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 11px;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--text-primary);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  margin-bottom: 8px;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 6px;
}

.must-diag .dlabel {
  color: var(--accent-red);
}

.diag-box .ddesc {
  font-size: 12px;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  line-height: 1.6;
  margin-top: 10px;
}

.diag-container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  background: #111110;
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 6px;
  padding: 12px;
  margin-top: 8px;
}

.diag-btn {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 4px;
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
  color: var(--text-primary);
  border-radius: 4px;
  padding: 6px 12px;
  font-size: 11px;
  font-weight: 600;
  text-decoration: none;
  margin-top: 10px;
  border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.04);
  transition: background 0.2s ease;
}

.diag-btn:hover {
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.12);
}

/* Comparison Tables */
.cmp-container {
  width: 100%;
  overflow-x: auto;
  margin: 12px 0;
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 8px;
}

.cmp {
  width: 100%;
  border-collapse: collapse;
  font-size: 12px;
  text-align: left;
}

.cmp th {
  background: #1f1f1e;
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--text-primary);
  padding: 10px 12px;
  border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border-color);
}

.cmp td {
  padding: 10px 12px;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  vertical-align: top;
}

.cmp tr:last-child td {
  border-bottom: none;
}

.cmp tr:nth-child(even) td {
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.01);
}

/* Q&A table inside answer boxes */
.qa-a table {
  width: 100%;
  border-collapse: collapse;
  font-size: 12px;
  margin: 10px 0;
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-green-border);
  border-radius: 6px;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.qa-a table th {
  background: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.15);
  color: var(--accent-green);
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-weight: 700;
  padding: 8px 10px;
  text-align: left;
}

.qa-a table td {
  padding: 8px 10px;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--accent-green-border);
  color: #d1fae5;
  background: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.02);
}

.qa-a table tr:last-child td {
  border-bottom: none;
}

/* Admonitions */
.tip {
  background: var(--accent-yellow-bg);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-yellow-border);
  border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-yellow);
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 12px 14px;
  margin: 12px 0;
  font-size: 13px;
  color: #fef08a;
}

.note {
  background: var(--accent-blue-bg);
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-blue-border);
  border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-blue);
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 12px 14px;
  margin: 12px 0;
  font-size: 13px;
  color: #93c5fd;
}

.sec-intro {
  background: var(--bg-card);
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 12px;
  padding: 14px 16px;
  margin-bottom: 16px;
  font-size: 13px;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  display: flex;
  gap: 12px;
  align-items: flex-start;
}

.sec-intro .icon {
  font-size: 20px;
  line-height: 1;
}

/* Key Section Header inside panel */
.sub-section-title {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 13px;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--text-primary);
  margin: 20px 0 10px;
  padding-top: 12px;
  border-top: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.04);
}

.sub-section-title:first-child {
  border-top: none;
  margin-top: 0;
  padding-top: 0;
}

/* Prose style */
.prose p {
  font-size: 13px;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}

.prose p:last-child {
  margin-bottom: 0;
}

.prose strong {
  color: var(--text-primary);
}

.prose ul, .prose ol {
  margin-left: 20px;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  font-size: 13px;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
}

.prose li {
  margin-bottom: 4px;
}

/* Circuit Diagrams */
.svg-diagram, .diagram-img {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 320px;
  height: auto;
  display: block;
  border-radius: 6px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
.diagram-img {
  filter: invert(0.92) hue-rotate(180deg) contrast(1.15) brightness(0.95);
}

/* Q&A layout for structured proofs/derivations */
.qa-block {
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 10px;
  margin: 14px 0;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.qa-q {
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.02);
  padding: 12px;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
}

.qa-q-title {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 9px;
  font-weight: 800;
  color: var(--accent-red);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  margin-bottom: 6px;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 6px;
}

.qa-q-text {
  font-family: var(--font-display);
  font-size: 13px;
  font-weight: 600;
  color: var(--text-primary);
}

.qa-a {
  border: none;
  border-radius: 0;
  margin: 0;
  background: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.03);
}

/* Scroll indicator warning for horizontal components */
.scroll-hint {
  font-size: 10px;
  color: var(--text-muted);
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 4px;
  margin-bottom: 4px;
}

@media(min-width: 640px) {
  .scroll-hint {
    display: none;
  }
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="top-bar">
  <h1>⚡ BEEE Study Dashboard v4</h1>
  <span class="subtitle">Modules 1, 2, 3, 4 &amp; 5 · UEC101T</span>
</div>

<div class="tab-bar-container">
  <div class="tab-bar">
    <button class="tab t2 active" onclick="show('m1',this)">🔌 MODULE 1</button>
    <button class="tab t2" onclick="show('m2',this)">📈 MODULE 2</button>
    <button class="tab t2" onclick="show('m3',this)">🔄 MODULE 3</button>
    <button class="tab t2" onclick="show('m4',this)">🔌 MODULE 4</button>
    <button class="tab t2" onclick="show('m5',this)">🌀 MODULE 5</button>
    <button class="tab t3" onclick="show('formulas',this)">📋 FORMULAS</button>
    <button class="tab t3" onclick="show('examtips',this)">⚠️ EXAM TIPS</button>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ==================== TAB: MODULE 1 ==================== -->
<div id="m1" class="panel active">
  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">🔌</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 1 — DC Circuits: Basic Concepts &amp; Kirchhoff's Laws</strong><br>
      KCL and KVL form the core equations for all network calculations. Make sure to master node identification and loop conventions.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Basic Concepts (Quick Recall)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t3">Basics</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p><strong>Electric Current (I):</strong> The flow of electrons through a conductor. Measured in Amperes (A).</p>
      <p><strong>Voltage (V):</strong> The electrical pressure that drives current through a circuit. Measured in Volts (V).</p>
      <p><strong>Resistance (R):</strong> Opposition offered to current flow. Measured in Ohms (Ω).</p>
      
      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Ohm's Law</div>
        <p><span class="f">V = IR</span></p>
        <p>Voltage = Current × Resistance. This is the foundation of every DC circuit calculation.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Series and Parallel Circuits Comparison</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Property</th>
              <th>Series</th>
              <th>Parallel</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Current</strong></td>
              <td>Same through all elements</td>
              <td>Divides across branches</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Voltage</strong></td>
              <td>Divides across elements</td>
              <td>Same across all parallel branches</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Total Resistance</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">R = R₁ + R₂ + R₃</span></td>
              <td><span class="f">1/R = 1/R₁ + 1/R₂ + 1/R₃</span></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Kirchhoff's Laws</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">KCL — Kirchhoff's Current Law</div>
        <p><strong>Statement:</strong> The total current entering a node equals the total current leaving it.</p>
        <p>In other words, charge cannot accumulate at a junction. Whatever comes in must go out.</p>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><span class="f">&Sigma; I_in = &Sigma; I_out</span></p>
      </div>

      <p><strong>How to apply:</strong></p>
      <ol>
        <li>Identify all nodes (junction points) in the circuit.</li>
        <li>At each node, write the KCL equation: currents entering = currents leaving.</li>
        <li>Solve the resulting simultaneous equations.</li>
      </ol>

      <p><strong>Sign Convention:</strong> Currents entering a node are positive (+). Currents leaving are negative (−). Or fix one convention and stick to it throughout.</p>
      <p><strong>Example:</strong> At a node, if <span class="f">I₁</span> and <span class="f">I₂</span> enter and <span class="f">I₃</span> leaves:<br>
      <span class="f">I_1 + I_2 = I_3</span></p>

      <div class="green-box" style="margin-top: 18px;">
        <div class="green-box-title">KVL — Kirchhoff's Voltage Law</div>
        <p><strong>Statement:</strong> The algebraic sum of all voltages around any closed loop in a circuit is zero.</p>
        <p>The idea is simple: if you start at any point in a circuit and travel around a complete loop back to the same point, the total voltage rise equals the total voltage drop.</p>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><span class="f">&Sigma; V = 0</span> (around any closed loop)</p>
      </div>

      <p><strong>How to apply (Mesh Analysis):</strong></p>
      <ol>
        <li>Assign mesh currents (<span class="f">I₁</span>, <span class="f">I₂</span>, ...) to each independent loop — usually clockwise.</li>
        <li>For each mesh, write KVL: sum of voltage drops = sum of EMF sources.</li>
        <li>Voltage drop across a resistor = <span class="f">I &times; R</span> (use the mesh current, or the difference if two meshes share a branch).</li>
        <li>Solve the equations simultaneously.</li>
      </ol>

      <p><strong>Sign Convention:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>When tracing a loop and you move through a resistor <strong>in the direction of assumed current</strong> &rarr; voltage drop = <span class="f">-IR</span></li>
        <li>When you move <strong>against current direction</strong> &rarr; voltage rise = <span class="f">+IR</span></li>
        <li>For a source: moving from &minus; to + is a voltage rise; + to &minus; is a drop.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Two-Mesh Example Setup</div>
      <p>For a standard two-loop circuit sharing a mutual resistor <span class="f">R_3</span>:</p>
      <p>For Loop 1: <span class="f">V_1 - I_1 R_1 - (I_1 - I_2) R_3 = 0</span></p>
      <p>For Loop 2: <span class="f">-I_2 R_2 - (I_2 - I_1) R_3 - V_2 = 0</span></p>
      <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Solve for <span class="f">I₁</span> and <span class="f">I₂</span> &rarr; use them to find branch currents and voltages.</p>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Forgetting to account for the shared branch current <span class="f">(I_1 - I_2)</span> when two mesh currents pass through the same resistor. The net current in a shared branch is always the algebraic difference of the two mesh currents.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q5c) Explain KCL and KVL with significance.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL):</strong><br>
          At any node (junction) in a circuit, the sum of all currents entering the node equals the sum of all currents leaving the node.</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            <div class="flabel">KCL Equation</div>
            <span class="formula-line">&Sigma;I(entering) = &Sigma;I(leaving)</span>
          </div>
          <p>Or equivalently: the algebraic sum of all currents at a node = 0.</p>
          
          <div class="diag-box">
            <div class="dlabel">KCL Junction & KVL Closed Loop Solved Diagram</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/kcl_kvl_solved.png" alt="KCL Node and KVL Loop Solved">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">Left: Junction node showing I₁ + I₂ = I₃ (Conservation of Charge). Right: Closed circuit loop showing V &minus; IR₁ &minus; IR₂ = 0 (Conservation of Energy).</div>
          </div>

          <p>This is based on the <strong>conservation of charge</strong> — charge cannot accumulate at a node.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Kirchhoff's Voltage Law (KVL):</strong><br>
          Around any closed loop in a circuit, the algebraic sum of all voltages (EMFs and voltage drops) equals zero.</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            <div class="flabel">KVL Equation</div>
            <span class="formula-line">&Sigma;V = 0</span>
          </div>
          <p>This is based on the <strong>conservation of energy</strong> — energy gained from sources equals energy lost across resistances.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Significance in circuit analysis:</strong><br>
          KCL and KVL are the foundation of all circuit analysis methods — mesh analysis, node voltage method, Thevenin's, Norton's, and superposition all derive their equations using these two laws. They apply to all linear and nonlinear circuits, DC or AC, and allow engineers to solve circuits of any complexity by writing simple algebraic equations.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">⚡</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 1 — Superposition Theorem</strong><br>
      Ideal for analyzing circuits with multiple independent sources. Remember: solve for one source at a time while deactivating all other sources.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">Superposition Theorem</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Theorem Statement</div>
        <p>In a circuit with <strong>multiple independent sources</strong>, the current (or voltage) at any element equals the <strong>algebraic sum</strong> of the contributions from each source acting alone.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">How to Apply (Step-by-Step)</div>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Take one source at a time.</strong> Leave one source active; deactivate all others.</li>
        <li><strong>Deactivating a source:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Voltage source &rarr; replace with a <strong>short circuit</strong> (wire)</li>
            <li>Current source &rarr; replace with an <strong>open circuit</strong> (remove it)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Find the current/voltage</strong> in the required element due to the active source.</li>
        <li><strong>Repeat</strong> for each remaining source.</li>
        <li><strong>Algebraically add</strong> all partial results. (Respect direction/sign — currents in the same direction add, opposite directions subtract.)</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Important Points</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Works only for <strong>linear circuits</strong> (circuits with resistors, linear inductors, capacitors — not diodes or transistors).</li>
        <li>Does NOT apply directly to <strong>power</strong> (power is not a linear quantity). Calculate current first, then find power.</li>
        <li>Each partial circuit is solved using basic Ohm's law and series/parallel rules.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Adding powers from each superposition step instead of adding currents/voltages. Always superpose the linear quantities, then calculate power at the end.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q5b) Superposition Theorem — find current through 20&Omega; resistor in the given circuit.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>Superposition theorem</strong> states that in a circuit with multiple sources, the current through any branch equals the algebraic sum of currents produced by each source acting independently, while all other sources are deactivated (voltage sources &rarr; shorted, current sources &rarr; open-circuited).</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>Circuit Parameters:</strong> 20V source, 5&Omega;, 10&Omega; (vertical middle branch), 10&Omega; (horizontal), 20&Omega;, and 4A current source.</p>
          
          <div class="diag-box">
            <div class="dlabel">Superposition Circuit Diagram</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/superposition_circuit_solved.png" alt="Superposition Circuit Solved">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">Linear network showing the 20V voltage source on the left, a 5&Omega; resistor, a 10&Omega; vertical branch, a 10&Omega; horizontal branch, a 20&Omega; load, and a 4A current source.</div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>Step 1 — Deactivate 4A source (open circuit it), keep 20V source:</strong><br>
          Using node analysis (<span class="f">V₂</span> = middle junction, <span class="f">V₃</span> = right node):<br>
          At <span class="f">V₃</span>: <span class="f">(V₂ &minus; V₃)/10 = V₃/20 &rarr; 2V₂ &minus; 2V₃ = V₃ &rarr; V₂ = 3V₃/2</span><br>
          At <span class="f">V₂</span>: <span class="f">(20 &minus; V₂)/5 = V₂/10 + (V₂ &minus; V₃)/10</span><br>
          Substituting <span class="f">V₂ = 3V₃/2</span> and solving:<br>
          <span class="f">40 = 5V₃ &rarr; V₃ = 8V</span><br>
          <span class="f">I'_{20} = V₃/20 = 8/20 = 0.4 A</span> (downward through 20&Omega;)</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Step 2 — Deactivate 20V source (short it), keep 4A source:</strong><br>
          With 20V shorted, 5&Omega; connects from the junction to ground.<br>
          Equivalent resistance from junction to ground:<br>
          <span class="f">5&Omega; &parallel; 10&Omega; = 10/3 &Omega;</span><br>
          At right node <span class="f">V₃</span>: 4A enters node. Two parallel paths to ground exist:<br>
          - Path 1: 20&Omega; directly<br>
          - Path 2: <span class="f">10&Omega; + 10/3 &Omega; = 40/3 &Omega;</span><br>
          <span class="f">Equivalent: 20 &parallel; (40/3) = (20 &times; 40/3)/(20 + 40/3) = (800/3)/(100/3) = 8&Omega;</span><br>
          <span class="f">V₃ = 4A &times; 8&Omega; = 32V</span><br>
          <span class="f">I''_{20} = 32/20 = 1.6 A</span> (downward through 20&Omega;)</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Final Answer:</strong><br>
          Both currents flow in the same direction (downward) through 20&Omega;:<br>
          <span class="f">I_{20} = I'_{20} + I''_{20} = 0.4 + 1.6 = 2 A</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">📐</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 1 — Thevenin's and Norton's Theorems</strong><br>
      These theorems simplify complex networks into simplified equivalents, making load current calculations simple.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Thevenin's Theorem</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Theorem Statement</div>
        <p>Any linear circuit with sources and resistors, viewed from two terminals (A and B), can be replaced by:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>A <strong>single voltage source</strong> <span class="f">V_th</span> (open-circuit voltage at A–B)</li>
          <li>In <strong>series</strong> with a <strong>single resistance</strong> <span class="f">R_th</span> (the equivalent resistance seen from A–B with all sources deactivated)</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;">This simplified circuit is called the <strong>Thevenin Equivalent Circuit</strong>.</p>
      </div>

      <p><strong>Why it's useful:</strong> When you need to find the current through a load for multiple load values, redoing the full circuit each time is inefficient. Thevenin reduces the whole network to one source + one resistor. Then finding <span class="f">I_L</span> for any <span class="f">R_L</span> is just one equation.</p>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Steps to Find Thevenin Equivalent</div>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Remove the load</strong> <span class="f">R_L</span> (open-circuit the terminals A and B).</li>
        <li><strong>Find V_th</strong> = voltage across the open terminals A–B (use KVL or voltage divider).</li>
        <li><strong>Deactivate all sources:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Voltage source &rarr; short circuit</li>
            <li>Current source &rarr; open circuit</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Find R_th</strong> = equivalent resistance seen from terminals A–B (with load removed and sources deactivated).</li>
        <li><strong>Draw the Thevenin equivalent:</strong> <span class="f">V_th</span> in series with <span class="f">R_th</span>, then reconnect <span class="f">R_L</span>.</li>
        <li><strong>Find load current:</strong></li>
      </ol>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Load Current Equation</div>
        <span class="formula-line">I_L = V_th / (R_th + R_L)</span>
      </div>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — Thevenin Equivalent Circuit</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <!-- SVG Diagram for Thevenin -->
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/thevenin_equivalent.png" alt="Thevenin Equivalent Circuit">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw a vertical DC source labeled V_th, in series with a resistor labeled R_th, leading to open terminal nodes A and B, across which the load resistor R_L is connected. Highlight terminals A and B.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=Thevenin+equivalent+circuit+diagram+labeled+Vth+Rth+RL&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: Thevenin Equivalent Circuit</a>
      </div>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Finding R_th without deactivating sources first. Voltage sources must be shorted and current sources must be opened before calculating R_th.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q1a) Recall the equivalent circuit of Thevenin's Theorem.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>Thevenin's theorem</strong> states that any linear circuit can be replaced by a single voltage source <strong>V_th</strong> (open-circuit voltage at the terminals) connected in series with a resistance <strong>R_th</strong> (the equivalent resistance seen from the terminals with all sources deactivated).</p>
          <div class="diag-box" style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <div class="dlabel">Thevenin Equivalent Circuit Diagram</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/thevenin_equivalent.png" alt="Thevenin Equivalent Circuit">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">A single loop with V_th as voltage source in series with R_th, connected to terminals A and B.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Norton's Theorem</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Theorem Statement</div>
        <p>Any linear circuit, viewed from two terminals, can be replaced by:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>A <strong>single current source</strong> <span class="f">I_N</span> (short-circuit current at A–B)</li>
          <li>In <strong>parallel</strong> with a <strong>single resistance</strong> <span class="f">R_N</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><span class="f">R_N</span> is found the exact same way as <span class="f">R_th</span>. In fact, <strong>R_N = R_th always</strong>.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Steps to Find Norton Equivalent</div>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Remove the load</strong> <span class="f">R_L</span>.</li>
        <li><strong>Short-circuit terminals A and B</strong> (put a wire across them).</li>
        <li><strong>Find I_N</strong> = current flowing through this short circuit (use KVL or current divider).</li>
        <li><strong>Find R_N</strong> = same method as <span class="f">R_th</span> (deactivate sources, find equivalent resistance from terminals).</li>
        <li><strong>Draw the Norton equivalent:</strong> <span class="f">I_N</span> in parallel with <span class="f">R_N</span>, then reconnect <span class="f">R_L</span>.</li>
        <li><strong>Find load current using current divider:</strong></li>
      </ol>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Load Current Equation (Current Divider)</div>
        <span class="formula-line">I_L = I_N * R_N / (R_N + R_L)</span>
      </div>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — Norton Equivalent Circuit</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <!-- SVG Diagram for Norton -->
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/norton_equivalent.png" alt="Norton Equivalent Circuit">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw a current source (circle with an upward arrow) in parallel with a resistor labeled R_N, leading to terminals A and B, across which the load R_L is connected.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=Norton+equivalent+circuit+diagram+labeled+IN+RN+RL&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: Norton Equivalent Circuit</a>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Relationship Between Thevenin and Norton (Source Transformation)</div>
        <p><span class="f">V_th = I_N * R_N</span></p>
        <p><span class="f">R_th = R_N</span></p>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;">Use these equations to quickly cross-check your values when solving network numericals.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Forgetting to short the terminals when finding <span class="f">I_N</span>. Many students find the open-circuit voltage instead of the short-circuit current — that gives <span class="f">V_th</span>, not <span class="f">I_N</span>.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q5d) Norton's Theorem — find current and voltage across RL = 1.5&Omega;.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>Norton's theorem</strong> states that any linear circuit can be replaced by an equivalent circuit consisting of a current source <strong>I_N</strong> in parallel with a resistance <strong>R_N</strong>, connected to the load terminals.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>Circuit:</strong> 12V source, 3&Omega; (left series), 6&Omega; (middle shunt), 3&Omega; (right series), R_L = 1.5&Omega; at terminals A–B.</p>
          
          <div class="diag-box">
            <div class="dlabel">Norton Original Circuit & Solved Equivalent Diagrams</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/norton_circuit_solved.png" alt="Norton Circuit Solved">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">Left: Original network showing 12V source, 3&Omega;, 6&Omega;, 3&Omega; resistors and load R_L = 1.5&Omega;. Right: Norton Equivalent showing parallel current source I_N = 1.6A, R_N = 5&Omega;, and load.</div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>Step 1 — Find Norton Current I_N (short A–B, find I_sc):</strong><br>
          With A–B shorted, the right 3&Omega; resistor connects the middle node directly to ground.<br>
          KCL at middle node (voltage = <span class="f">V₁</span>):<br>
          <span class="f">(12 &minus; V₁)/3 = V₁/6 + V₁/3</span><br>
          Multiply through by 6:<br>
          <span class="f">2(12 &minus; V₁) = V₁ + 2V₁ &rarr; 24 &minus; 2V₁ = 3V₁ &rarr; V₁ = 4.8V</span><br>
          <span class="f">I_N = I_sc = V₁/3 = 4.8/3 = 1.6 A</span></p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Step 2 — Find Norton Resistance R_N (deactivate 12V source, short it):</strong><br>
          Looking into terminals A–B with source shorted, left 3&Omega; is in parallel with 6&Omega;:<br>
          <span class="f">3 &parallel; 6 = (3 &times; 6)/(3 + 6) = 2&Omega;</span><br>
          This 2&Omega; is in series with the right 3&Omega;:<br>
          <span class="f">R_N = 2 + 3 = 5&Omega;</span></p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Step 3 — Draw Norton equivalent and solve:</strong><br>
          Using current divider:<br>
          <span class="f">I_L = I_N &times; R_N / (R_N + R_L) = 1.6 &times; 5 / (5 + 1.5) = 8/6.5 = 1.23 A</span><br>
          <span class="f">V_L = I_L &times; R_L = 1.23 &times; 1.5 = 1.85 V</span></p>

          <div class="cmp-container" style="margin-top: 12px;">
            <table class="cmp">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Parameter</th>
                  <th>Value</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Norton Current (I_N)</strong></td>
                  <td>1.6 A</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Norton Resistance (R_N)</strong></td>
                  <td>5 &Omega;</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Load Current (I_L)</strong></td>
                  <td>1.23 A</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Load Voltage (V_L)</strong></td>
                  <td>1.85 V</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">3. Comparison of the Three Theorems</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t3">Reference Table</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body">
      <div class="scroll-hint">Swipe horizontally to view comparison table &rarr;</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Feature</th>
              <th>Superposition</th>
              <th>Thevenin</th>
              <th>Norton</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Purpose</strong></td>
              <td>Find response due to multiple sources</td>
              <td>Simplify circuit to one voltage source + R</td>
              <td>Simplify circuit to one current source + R</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Equivalent Circuit</strong></td>
              <td>No single equivalent — sum of parts</td>
              <td><span class="f">V_th</span> in series with <span class="f">R_th</span></td>
              <td><span class="f">I_N</span> in parallel with <span class="f">R_N</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>When to use</strong></td>
              <td>Multiple independent sources</td>
              <td>Finding current for various load values</td>
              <td>Same as Thevenin; dual form</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Key calculation</strong></td>
              <td>Partial currents for each active source</td>
              <td><span class="f">V_th</span> (open circuit), <span class="f">R_th</span> (deactivated)</td>
              <td><span class="f">I_N</span> (short circuit), <span class="f">R_N</span> (deactivated)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Relationship</strong></td>
              <td>Independent</td>
              <td><span class="f">R_th = V_th / I_N</span></td>
              <td><span class="f">R_N = R_th</span></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ==================== TAB: MODULE 2 ==================== -->
<div id="m2" class="panel">
  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">📈</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 2 — AC Circuits: Fundamentals</strong><br>
      AC voltages and currents alternate direction in sinusoidal patterns. Standard parameters like RMS and average values govern power delivery.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. What is Alternating Current?</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t3">Basics</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>DC (Direct Current) flows in one fixed direction. AC (Alternating Current) reverses direction periodically — it keeps swinging back and forth in a sinusoidal pattern.</p>
      
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Standard Sinusoidal Form</div>
        <span class="formula-line">v(t) = V_m * sin(&omega;t + &phi;)</span>
      </div>

      <p>Where:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>V_m</strong> = Peak (maximum) voltage</li>
        <li><strong>&omega;</strong> = Angular frequency = <span class="f">2&pi;f</span> (rad/s)</li>
        <li><strong>f</strong> = Frequency in Hz</li>
        <li><strong>&phi;</strong> = Phase angle (initial phase shift)</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q1c) Irms = 6A, R = 40&Omega; — find average voltage and peak voltage.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><span class="f">V_rms = I_rms &times; R = 6 &times; 40 = 240 V</span></p>
          <p><span class="f">V_peak = V_rms &times; &radic;2 = 240 &times; 1.414 = 339.4 V</span></p>
          <p><span class="f">V_avg = 0.637 &times; V_peak = 0.637 &times; 339.4 = 216.1 V</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q1d) Write equation for sinusoidal current: f = 25 Hz, Irms = 20A.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><span class="f">I_m = I_rms &times; &radic;2 = 20 &times; 1.414 = 28.28 A</span></p>
          <p><span class="f">&omega; = 2&pi;f = 2&pi; &times; 25 = 50&pi; rad/s</span></p>
          <div class="formula-box" style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <div class="flabel">Sinusoidal Current Equation</div>
            <span class="formula-line">i = 28.28 sin(50&pi;t) A</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Key AC Terms</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body">
      <div class="scroll-hint">Swipe horizontally &rarr;</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Term</th>
              <th>Symbol</th>
              <th>Meaning</th>
              <th>Formula</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Frequency</strong></td>
              <td>f</td>
              <td>Number of complete cycles per second</td>
              <td><span class="f">f = 1/T</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Time Period</strong></td>
              <td>T</td>
              <td>Time for one complete cycle</td>
              <td><span class="f">T = 1/f</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Angular Frequency</strong></td>
              <td>&omega;</td>
              <td>Rate of change of angle in radians</td>
              <td><span class="f">&omega; = 2&pi;f</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Peak Value</strong></td>
              <td>V_m / I_m</td>
              <td>Maximum value in either direction</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Phase</strong></td>
              <td>&phi;</td>
              <td>Starting angle of the waveform at t = 0</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Phase Difference</strong></td>
              <td>&theta;</td>
              <td>Angle by which one quantity leads/lags another</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: 12px; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-top: 10px;" class="prose">
        In India, the mains supply is <strong>50 Hz</strong>, so <span class="f">T = 20 ms</span> and <span class="f">&omega; = 314 rad/s</span>.
      </p>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q1b) Define impedance in AC circuits. Give its units.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>Impedance (Z)</strong> is the total opposition offered by a circuit to the flow of alternating current. It includes both resistance (R) and reactance (inductive <span class="f">X_L</span> or capacitive <span class="f">X_C</span>). It is measured in <strong>Ohms (&Omega;)</strong>.</p>
          <div class="formula-box" style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <div class="flabel">Impedance Formula</div>
            <span class="formula-line">Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X&sup2;)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q2 — Option 2: Define AC Terms in Detail.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>i. Instantaneous Value:</strong><br>
          The value of an alternating quantity (voltage or current) at any specific instant of time. It keeps changing every moment as the waveform cycles. Represented as <span class="f">v = V_m sin(&omega;t)</span> where the value depends on the time t you pick.</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>ii. Peak-to-Peak Value:</strong><br>
          The total voltage swing from the maximum positive value to the maximum negative value in one complete cycle. If peak value is <span class="f">V_m</span>, then:<br>
          <span class="f">Peak-to-peak value = 2V_m</span><br>
          For example, if <span class="f">V_m = 20V</span>, the peak-to-peak value is 40V.</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>iii. Average Value:</strong><br>
          The mean of all instantaneous values over one half-cycle of the AC waveform (taken over half cycle because the full cycle averages to zero for a sinusoidal wave).<br>
          <span class="f">V_avg = 0.637 &times; V_m = (2/&pi;) &times; V_m</span></p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>iv. Equation for sinusoidal voltage — f = 50 Hz, V_m = 20V:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">v = V_m sin(2&pi;ft) = 20 sin(2&pi; &times; 50 &times; t)</span><br>
          <span class="f">v = 20 sin(100&pi;t) Volts</span></p>

          <div class="diag-box">
            <div class="dlabel">Sinusoidal AC Waveform Solved Graph</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/sinusoidal_graph_solved.png" alt="Sinusoidal Voltage Waveform Graph">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">Voltage vs time grid graph showing one full 20 ms cycle (f=50Hz) with peak amplitude +20V (peak-to-peak = 40V), zero crossings, and time increments.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">3. RMS and Average Values</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">RMS (Root Mean Square) Value</div>
        <p><strong>Definition:</strong> The DC equivalent of an AC quantity — the value of DC that would produce the same heating effect as the AC in the same resistance.</p>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;">Because AC voltage is always changing, we use the RMS value for power calculations. RMS gives you the "effective" value.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">RMS Formulas</div>
        <span class="formula-line">V_rms = V_m / &radic;2 &approx; 0.707 * V_m</span>
        <span class="formula-line">I_rms = I_m / &radic;2 &approx; 0.707 * I_m</span>
      </div>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Exam Point:</strong> The 230 V of your home supply is the RMS value, not the peak. The actual peak is <span class="f">230 &times; &radic;2 &approx; 325 V</span>.
      </div>

      <div class="green-box" style="margin-top: 18px;">
        <div class="green-box-title">Average Value</div>
        <p>The average of a full AC cycle is <strong>zero</strong> (positive and negative halves cancel). So average value is calculated over a <strong>half cycle</strong> only.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Average Value Formulas</div>
        <span class="formula-line">V_avg = 2 * V_m / &pi; &approx; 0.637 * V_m</span>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Form Factor and Peak Factor</div>
      <p>These are ratios used to describe the shape of a waveform.</p>
      <p><strong>Form Factor</strong> = RMS / Average = <span class="f">0.707 / 0.637 = 1.11</span></p>
      <p><strong>Peak Factor (Crest Factor)</strong> = Peak / RMS = <span class="f">V_m / (V_m/&radic;2) = &radic;2 &approx; 1.414</span></p>
      
      <div class="tip" style="margin-top: 8px;">
        <strong>Note:</strong> These values (1.11 and 1.414) are standard for a pure sinusoidal waveform. If the waveform changes shape, these values change too.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q3 — Option 1: Derive RMS value of alternating current in terms of maximum value.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>RMS (Root Mean Square)</strong> value is the DC equivalent value of an AC current — the steady DC that would produce the same heating effect in a resistor.</p>
          <p><strong>1. Expression for instantaneous current:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">i = I_m sin(&omega;t)</span></p>
          <p><strong>2. Square of instantaneous current:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">i&sup2; = I_m&sup2; sin&sup2;(&omega;t)</span></p>
          <p><strong>3. Mean value of i&sup2; over one full cycle:</strong><br>
          Using the identity: <span class="f">sin&sup2;(&omega;t)</span> averaged over a full cycle = 1/2<br>
          <span class="f">Mean of i&sup2; = I_m&sup2; / 2</span></p>
          <p><strong>4. Take square root to get RMS:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">I_rms = &radic;(I_m&sup2; / 2) = I_m / &radic;2</span><br>
          <span class="f">I_rms = 0.707 &times; I_m</span></p>
          <p>This is the most important result in AC theory. It means the RMS value is always 70.7% of the peak value.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Significance:</strong> When we say household supply is 230V, that is the RMS value. The actual peak voltage is <span class="f">230 &times; &radic;2 &approx; 325V</span>. All AC meters read RMS values.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">4. Phasor Representation</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t3">Tier 3</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>AC quantities like voltage and current vary sinusoidally with time. Representing them on a time graph is messy when multiple quantities are involved.</p>
      <p>A <strong>phasor</strong> is a rotating vector that represents the magnitude and phase of a sinusoidal quantity. You freeze the rotation at <span class="f">t = 0</span> and draw it as an arrow.</p>
      <p><strong>Why it's useful:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Instead of writing <span class="f">v = V_m sin(&omega;t + 30&deg;)</span>, you draw a vector of length <span class="f">V_m</span> at 30&deg;.</li>
        <li>Adding two AC voltages becomes vector addition instead of trigonometric addition.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Key rules:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>A quantity that <strong>leads</strong> another is drawn at a <strong>higher angle</strong> (anti-clockwise).</li>
        <li>A quantity that <strong>lags</strong> is drawn at a <strong>lower angle</strong> (clockwise).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">🌀</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 2 — Pure R, L, and C Circuits</strong><br>
      The individual components behave differently under AC excitation, exhibiting unique relationships between voltage, current, and reactance.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">Pure Resistive Circuit (R only)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t3">Basics</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>When only resistance is in the circuit:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Voltage and current are <strong>in phase</strong> (&phi; = 0&deg;).</li>
        <li>No reactive energy storage — all energy is consumed as heat.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Impedance:</strong> <span class="f">Z = R</span></p>
      <p><strong>Phasor Diagram:</strong> V and I vectors point in the same direction.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">Pure Inductive Circuit (L only)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>An inductor opposes changes in current. When AC flows through it:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Current <strong>lags</strong> voltage by <strong>90&deg;</strong>.</li>
        <li>The opposition offered by an inductor is called <strong>Inductive Reactance</strong> (<span class="f">X_L</span>).</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Inductive Reactance Equation</div>
        <span class="formula-line">X_L = &omega;L = 2&pi;fL (&Omega;)</span>
      </div>

      <p>Higher the frequency, higher the opposition (inductor blocks high-frequency AC more).</p>
      <p><strong>Impedance:</strong> <span class="f">Z = X_L = j&omega;L</span></p>
      <p><strong>Memory tip:</strong> <em>ELI</em> — In an inductive (L) circuit, E (voltage) comes before I (current) &rarr; current lags voltage.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">Pure Capacitive Circuit (C only)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>A capacitor opposes changes in voltage. When AC flows through it:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Current <strong>leads</strong> voltage by <strong>90&deg;</strong>.</li>
        <li>The opposition offered is called <strong>Capacitive Reactance</strong> (<span class="f">X_C</span>).</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Capacitive Reactance Equation</div>
        <span class="formula-line">X_C = 1/(&omega;C) = 1/(2&pi;fC) (&Omega;)</span>
      </div>

      <p>Higher the frequency, lower the opposition (capacitor passes high-frequency AC easily).</p>
      <p><strong>Impedance:</strong> <span class="f">Z = X_C = -j/(&omega;C)</span></p>
      <p><strong>Memory tip:</strong> <em>ICE</em> — In a capacitive (C) circuit, I (current) comes before E (voltage) &rarr; current leads voltage.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">Component Response Summary</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t3">Quick Reference</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body">
      <div class="scroll-hint">Swipe horizontally &rarr;</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Property</th>
              <th>Resistor (R)</th>
              <th>Inductor (L)</th>
              <th>Capacitor (C)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Opposition</strong></td>
              <td>Resistance <span class="f">R</span></td>
              <td>Reactance <span class="f">X_L = &omega;L</span></td>
              <td>Reactance <span class="f">X_C = 1/&omega;C</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Phase Relation</strong></td>
              <td>V and I in phase</td>
              <td>I lags V by 90&deg;</td>
              <td>I leads V by 90&deg;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Power Consumed</strong></td>
              <td>Yes (active power)</td>
              <td>No (purely reactive)</td>
              <td>No (purely reactive)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Frequency Effect</strong></td>
              <td>No change</td>
              <td><span class="f">X_L</span> increases with f</td>
              <td><span class="f">X_C</span> decreases with f</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">⚡</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 2 — RL, RC, &amp; RLC Series Circuits</strong><br>
      Series combinations create phase shifts that lie between 0&deg; and 90&deg;. Resonance occurs when inductive and capacitive reactances cancel out.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. RL Series Circuit</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      
      <p>A resistor and inductor connected in series with an AC supply. The resistor consumes active power while the inductor stores and returns reactive power.</p>
      <p><strong>What happens:</strong> Current lags behind voltage by some angle &phi; (between 0&deg; and 90&deg;).</p>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Impedance Triangle &amp; Phase Angle</div>
      <p>The voltage across R (<span class="f">V_R</span>) and voltage across L (<span class="f">V_L</span>) are at 90&deg; to each other. Total voltage is their vector sum:</p>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">RL Series Equations</div>
        <span class="formula-line">V = &radic;(V_R&sup2; + V_L&sup2;)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X_L&sup2;) (&Omega;)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">&phi; = tan&minus;&sup1;(X_L / R)  [Current Lags]</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Power Factor = cos &phi; = R/Z</span>
      </div>

      <div class="scroll-hint">Swipe horizontally &rarr;</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Quantity</th>
              <th>Formula</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Inductive Reactance</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">X_L = 2&pi;fL</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Impedance</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X_L&sup2;)</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Current</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">I = V/Z</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Voltage across R</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">V_R = IR</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Voltage across L</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">V_L = IX_L</span></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — RL Phasor &amp; Impedance Triangle</div>
        <div style="display: flex; gap: 16px; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center;">
          <!-- SVG: RL Phasor -->
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/rl_phasor.png" alt="RL Series Phasor Diagram">
          
          <!-- SVG: Impedance Triangle -->
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/rl_impedance.png" alt="RL Series Impedance Triangle">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw current I along the X-axis. Draw V_R in phase, V_L pointing vertically up, and the diagonal resultant V. The impedance triangle follows the same orientation (R, X_L, Z).</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=RL+series+circuit+impedance+triangle+phasor+diagram&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: RL Series Diagrams</a>
      </div>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Adding V_R and V_L directly as numbers. They must be added as perpendicular vectors. <span class="f">V &ne; V_R + V_L</span>.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q2 — Option 1: Summarize the analysis of RL circuit.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>In a series <strong>RL circuit</strong>, a resistor R and an inductor L are connected in series to an AC supply of voltage V.</p>
          
          <div class="diag-box">
            <div class="dlabel">Series RL Circuit & Phasor Solved Diagram</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/rl_circuit_solved.png" alt="Series RL Circuit Phasor Diagram">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">Left: Series loop of R and L connected to AC source V. Right: Phasor diagram showing V_R in phase with current Reference vector I, V_L leading by 90&deg;, and total resultant V at phase lag &phi;.</div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>1. Voltage relationships:</strong><br>
          The voltage across R is <span class="f">V_R = IR</span>, which is in phase with the current. The voltage across L is <span class="f">V_L = IX_L</span>, which leads the current by 90°. Since these are 90° apart, total voltage is found by phasor addition:<br>
          <span class="f">V = &radic;(V_R&sup2; + V_L&sup2;)</span></p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Impedance:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X_L&sup2;)</span>, where <span class="f">X_L = 2&pi;fL</span> is the inductive reactance in Ohms.</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>3. Phase angle:</strong><br>
          The current lags the supply voltage by angle &phi;, where:<br>
          <span class="f">tan &phi; = X_L / R &rarr; &phi; = tan&minus;&sup1;(X_L / R)</span></p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>4. Power factor:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">cos &phi; = R/Z</span> (lagging, since current lags voltage in an inductive circuit)</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>5. Current:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">I = V/Z</span></p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Key point:</strong> The higher the frequency, the greater <span class="f">X_L</span> becomes, so the circuit becomes more inductive and the phase lag increases.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. RC Series Circuit</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">

      <p>A resistor and capacitor connected in series with an AC supply.</p>
      <p><strong>What happens:</strong> Current leads voltage by angle &phi; (between 0&deg; and 90&deg;).</p>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">RC Series Equations</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X_C&sup2;)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">X_C = 1 / (2&pi;fC)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">&phi; = tan&minus;&sup1;(X_C / R) [Current Leads]</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Power Factor = cos &phi; = R/Z</span>
      </div>

      <div class="scroll-hint">Swipe horizontally &rarr;</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Quantity</th>
              <th>Formula</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Capacitive Reactance</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">X_C = 1 / (2&pi;fC)</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Impedance</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X_C&sup2;)</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Current</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">I = V/Z</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Voltage across R</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">V_R = IR</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Voltage across C</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">V_C = IX_C</span></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — RC Phasor &amp; Impedance Triangle</div>
        <div style="display: flex; gap: 16px; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center;">
          <!-- SVG: RC Phasor -->
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/rc_phasor.png" alt="RC Series Phasor Diagram">
          
          <!-- SVG: RC Impedance Triangle -->
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/rc_impedance.png" alt="RC Series Impedance Triangle">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw current I along the X-axis. Draw V_R in phase, V_C pointing vertically down, and resultant V in the 4th quadrant. The impedance triangle mirrors this.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=RC+series+circuit+impedance+triangle+phasor+diagram&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: RC Series Diagrams</a>
      </div>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Common Mistake:</strong> In RC circuits, the capacitive voltage V_C and capacitive reactance X_C must be drawn pointing downwards (negative Y-axis), not upwards.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q3 — Option 2: Impedance and power factor of an RC circuit.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>In a series <strong>RC circuit</strong>, a resistor R and capacitor C are connected in series to an AC supply.</p>
          
          <div class="diag-box">
            <div class="dlabel">Series RC Circuit & Phasor Solved Diagram</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/rc_circuit_solved.png" alt="Series RC Circuit Phasor Diagram">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">Left: Series loop of R and C connected to AC source V. Right: Phasor diagram showing current I leading V_C by 90&deg;, V_R in phase with Reference current I, and resultant V in the 4th quadrant (lagging current).</div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>1. Voltage across R:</strong> <span class="f">V_R = IR</span> (in phase with current)</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Voltage across C:</strong> <span class="f">V_C = IX_C</span>, where <span class="f">X_C = 1/(2&pi;fC)</span> — this lags the current by 90°</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>3. Capacitive Reactance:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">X_C = 1 / (2&pi;fC)</span><br>
          As frequency increases, <span class="f">X_C</span> decreases — a capacitor passes high-frequency AC more easily.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>4. Impedance:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X_C&sup2;)</span></p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>5. Phase angle:</strong><br>
          The current leads the voltage by angle &phi; (opposite of RL circuit):<br>
          <span class="f">tan &phi; = X_C / R &rarr; &phi; = tan&minus;&sup1;(X_C / R)</span><br>
          Current leads voltage in a capacitive circuit.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>6. Power Factor:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">cos &phi; = R/Z</span> (leading)</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;">The power factor tells how much of the apparent power is actually doing useful work. A PF of 1 means pure resistive circuit; PF close to 0 means mostly reactive (no real power consumed).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">3. RLC Series Circuit &amp; Resonance</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t3">Tier 3</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>Contains R, L, and C all in series. The inductive and capacitive reactances oppose each other directly.</p>
      
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">RLC Series Impedance</div>
        <span class="formula-line">X_net = X_L - X_C</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + (X_L - X_C)&sup2;)</span>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Three Possible Conditions</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Condition</th>
              <th>Circuit Behaviour</th>
              <th>Phase Relation</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>X_L &gt; X_C</strong></td>
              <td>Inductive circuit dominates</td>
              <td>Current lags voltage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>X_C &gt; X_L</strong></td>
              <td>Capacitive circuit dominates</td>
              <td>Current leads voltage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>X_L = X_C</strong></td>
              <td><strong>Resonance</strong> condition</td>
              <td>Current and voltage in phase (Z = R minimum)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box" style="margin-top: 18px;">
        <div class="green-box-title">Resonance Frequency</div>
        <p>At resonance, the net reactance is zero. The impedance is purely resistive and is at its absolute minimum value, causing maximum current flow.</p>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><span class="f">f_r = 1 / (2&pi;&radic;(LC))</span></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">📐</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 2 — Power in AC Circuits &amp; The Power Triangle</strong><br>
      AC circuits convey active power (converted to work) and reactive power (stored). They form a right triangle whose hypotenuse is apparent power.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Power in AC Circuits</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>Unlike DC circuits where <span class="f">P = VI</span>, AC circuits must account for the phase difference &phi; between voltage and current waveforms.</p>
      
      <p><strong>Active Power (Real Power) — P:</strong> The actual power consumed to do useful work (heat, light, mechanical motion). Unit: <strong>Watt (W)</strong></p>
      <p><span class="f">P = VI cos &phi; = I&sup2;R</span></p>
      
      <p><strong>Reactive Power — Q:</strong> The power stored and returned by inductors/capacitors. It does no real work. Unit: <strong>Volt-Ampere Reactive (VAR)</strong></p>
      <p><span class="f">Q = VI sin &phi; = I&sup2;X</span></p>
      
      <p><strong>Apparent Power — S:</strong> The total raw power supplied by the generator. Unit: <strong>Volt-Ampere (VA)</strong></p>
      <p><span class="f">S = VI = I&sup2;Z</span></p>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Power Relationship</div>
        <span class="formula-line">S&sup2; = P&sup2; + Q&sup2;</span>
        <span class="formula-line">S = &radic;(P&sup2; + Q&sup2;)</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. The Power Triangle</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      
      <p>The three components of AC power form a right-angled triangle:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Horizontal Leg:</strong> P (Active Power, Watts)</li>
        <li><strong>Vertical Leg:</strong> Q (Reactive Power, VAR)</li>
        <li><strong>Hypotenuse:</strong> S (Apparent Power, VA)</li>
        <li><strong>Angle &phi;:</strong> Phase angle between voltage and current</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — Power Triangle</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <!-- SVG: Power Triangle -->
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/power_triangle.png" alt="AC Power Triangle">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw the horizontal base representing P, vertical height representing Q, and hypotenuse representing S. Clearly label the phase angle &phi; at the origin and supply the units.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=Power+triangle+AC+circuits+active+reactive+apparent+power&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: Power Triangle Diagrams</a>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Power Factor (cos &phi;)</div>
        <p><span class="f">cos &phi; = P / S = R / Z</span></p>
        <p>Power factor indicates how efficiently a circuit utilizes the supplied electrical power.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>PF = 1 (Unity):</strong> Purely resistive load &rarr; all current does active work.</li>
          <li><strong>PF = 0:</strong> Purely reactive load &rarr; no active work is performed.</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>Lag/Lead:</strong> For RL series circuits, current lags voltage (<strong>lagging PF</strong>). For RC series circuits, current leads voltage (<strong>leading PF</strong>).</p>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q5a) Power triangle — active, reactive, and apparent power.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>In any AC circuit containing resistance and reactance, three types of power exist simultaneously:</p>
          
          <div class="diag-box">
            <div class="dlabel">AC Power Triangle Diagram</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/power_triangle.png" alt="AC Power Triangle Solved">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">Right-angled triangle with horizontal side labeled P (Active Power, Watts), vertical side labeled Q (Reactive Power, VAR), hypotenuse S (Apparent Power, VA), phase angle &phi;.</div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>1. Active Power (P):</strong><br>
          Also called real power or true power. This is the power actually consumed and converted to heat, light, or mechanical work.<br>
          <span class="f">P = VI cos &phi;</span> &nbsp;&nbsp; (unit: Watts, W)</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Reactive Power (Q):</strong><br>
          Power that oscillates between source and reactive components (inductors and capacitors) without doing useful work.<br>
          <span class="f">Q = VI sin &phi;</span> &nbsp;&nbsp; (unit: Volt-Ampere Reactive, VAR)</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>3. Apparent Power (S):</strong><br>
          The total power supplied by the source — the product of RMS voltage and current, without considering phase.<br>
          <span class="f">S = VI</span> &nbsp;&nbsp; (unit: Volt-Ampere, VA)</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>4. Relationship (Pythagoras applied to power):</strong><br>
          <span class="f">S&sup2; = P&sup2; + Q&sup2;</span></p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>5. Power Factor:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">cos &phi; = P/S = Active Power / Apparent Power</span></p>
          <p style="margin-top: 6px;">A power factor of 1 means all power is active (purely resistive). A low power factor means most power is reactive — inefficient. Power factor correction (using capacitors) is done in industries to bring PF close to 1.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ==================== TAB: FORMULAS ==================== -->
<div id="formulas" class="panel">
  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">📋</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Combined Formula Reference Sheets</strong><br>
      Quick equations index for Module 1 (DC Circuits &amp; Network Theorems), Module 2 (AC Circuits), and Module 3 (Electrical Machines).
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 1 — DC Circuit Formulas</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Ohm's Law &amp; Basics</div>
        <span class="formula-line">V = I * R</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Series: R_eq = R_1 + R_2 + R_3</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Parallel: 1/R_eq = 1/R_1 + 1/R_2 + 1/R_3</span>
      </div>
      
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Kirchhoff's Laws</div>
        <span class="formula-line">KCL: &Sigma; I_in = &Sigma; I_out</span>
        <span class="formula-line">KVL: &Sigma; V = 0  (Around closed mesh loop)</span>
      </div>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Network Equivalent Formulas</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Thevenin Current: I_L = V_th / (R_th + R_L)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Norton Current (Divider): I_L = I_N * R_N / (R_N + R_L)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Source Conversion: V_th = I_N * R_N  (R_th = R_N)</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 2 — AC Circuit Formulas</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Sinusoidal Values &amp; Wave Ratios</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Effective / RMS Value: V_rms = V_m / &radic;2 &approx; 0.707 * V_m</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Average Value (Half-Cycle): V_avg = 2 * V_m / &pi; &approx; 0.637 * V_m</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Form Factor: K_f = RMS / Average = 1.11  (Sine wave)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Peak Factor: K_p = Peak / RMS = 1.414  (Sine wave)</span>
      </div>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Reactance &amp; Impedances</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Inductive Reactance: X_L = 2&pi;fL</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Capacitive Reactance: X_C = 1 / (2&pi;fC)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">RL Impedance: Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X_L&sup2;)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">RC Impedance: Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + X_C&sup2;)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">RLC Impedance: Z = &radic;(R&sup2; + (X_L - X_C)&sup2;)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Resonance Frequency: f_r = 1 / (2&pi;&radic;(LC))</span>
      </div>

      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Power &amp; Power Factor</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Active Power: P = VI cos &phi; = I&sup2;R  (W)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Reactive Power: Q = VI sin &phi; = I&sup2;X  (VAR)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Apparent Power: S = VI = I&sup2;Z  (VA)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Power Triangle: S = &radic;(P&sup2; + Q&sup2;)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Power Factor: cos &phi; = P/S = R/Z</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 3 — Electrical Machines Formulas</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Transformer Equations</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Turns Ratio: V_1 / V_2 = N_1 / N_2 = I_2 / I_1</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Efficiency: &eta; = (Output Power / Input Power) * 100%</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Ideal Transformer: &eta; = 100%  &rarr;  V_1 I_1 = V_2 I_2</span>
      </div>
      
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">3-Phase Induction Motor Equations</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Synchronous Speed: N_s = 120f / P  (RPM)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Fractional Slip: s = (N_s - N) / N_s</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Percentage Slip: s% = [ (N_s - N) / N_s ] * 100</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Rotor Speed: N = N_s * (1 - s)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Rotor Standstill: N = 0  &rarr;  s = 1 (100% slip)</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 4 — Electrical Installations Limits &amp; Specifications</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Breaker &amp; Earthing Ratings</div>
        <span class="formula-line">MCB Max Current Rating: I_max &le; 100 A</span>
        <span class="formula-line">ELCB Leakage Trip Threshold: I_leak = 30 mA  (0.03 A)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">ELCB Maximum Trip Time: t_trip = 30 ms  (0.03 s)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Target Earthing Resistance: R_earth &lt; 1 &Omega;</span>
        <span class="formula-line">GI Pipe Dimensions: Diameter &ge; 38 mm, Burial Depth &ge; 2.5 m</span>
      </div>
      
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Cable Insulation Temperature Limits</div>
        <span class="formula-line">PVC (Polyvinyl Chloride) Max Continuous Temp: 70&deg;C</span>
        <span class="formula-line">XLPE (Cross-Linked Polyethylene) Max Continuous Temp: 90&deg;C</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 5 — Transducers &amp; LVDT Equations</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">LVDT Output &amp; Operation</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Differential AC Output Voltage: E_out = E_1 - E_2</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Null Position: E_1 = E_2  &rarr;  E_out = 0 V</span>
        <span class="formula-line">S1 Displacement (Positive): E_1 &gt; E_2  &rarr;  E_out is positive (in-phase with supply)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">S2 Displacement (Negative): E_2 &gt; E_1  &rarr;  E_out is negative (180&deg; out-of-phase)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">LVDT Sensitivity: S = E_out / Displacement  (mV/mm)</span>
      </div>
      
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Transducer Classification Principles</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Active (Self-Generating): Output = EMF (Thermocouple, Piezoelectric, Photovoltaic)</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Passive (External Excitation): &Delta;R, &Delta;L, or &Delta;C (LVDT, Thermistor, Strain Gauge)</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ==================== TAB: MODULE 3 ==================== -->
<div id="m3" class="panel">
  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">🔄</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 3 — Electrical Machines: Transformers</strong><br>
      Transformers transfer electrical energy via electromagnetic induction without moving parts. Focus on construction, turns ratio, and DC failure.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Transformer Construction &amp; Working</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>A transformer transfers electrical energy from one circuit to another using electromagnetic induction — <strong>without any electrical contact</strong> between the two circuits. It can increase (step-up) or decrease (step-down) the AC voltage.</p>
      
      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Faraday's Law of Induction</div>
        <p>A changing magnetic flux induces an electromotive force (EMF) in a nearby coil. This is the governing physical principle of transformers.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Construction details</div>
      <p>A transformer has three main parts:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Primary coil (winding):</strong> The input coil, connected to the AC supply.</li>
        <li><strong>Secondary coil (winding):</strong> The output coil, connected to the load.</li>
        <li><strong>Iron core:</strong> Made of laminated silicon steel. It carries the magnetic flux from primary to secondary.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Why laminated core?</strong> Thin laminations reduce <strong>eddy current losses</strong> (heat wastage inside the iron core) by breaking up circulating current paths.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q1e) Name materials used for transformer core and windings.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>Core:</strong> Silicon steel (soft iron laminated sheets) — used because it has high permeability and low hysteresis loss.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong>Windings:</strong> Copper — used because of its low resistivity and good conductivity.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — Single-Phase Transformer Core &amp; Windings</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/transformer_core.png" alt="Transformer Construction Core & Windings">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw a rectangular steel frame. Wrap winding coils around the left leg (Primary N₁) and right leg (Secondary N₂). Draw a dashed red flux loop through the center of the core. Highlight lamination layers.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=single+phase+transformer+core+and+winding+diagram+labeled&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: Transformer Core Diagram</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Working Principle</div>
      <p>When AC flows through the primary coil, it creates a <strong>continuously changing magnetic flux</strong> in the iron core. This changing flux links with the secondary winding and induces an EMF in it via <strong>mutual induction</strong>.</p>
      
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Transformer Transformation Ratio</div>
        <span class="formula-line">V_1 / V_2 = N_1 / N_2 = I_2 / I_1</span>
      </div>

      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Variable</th>
              <th>Meaning</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>V₁, V₂</strong></td>
              <td>Primary and secondary terminal voltages (V)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>N₁, N₂</strong></td>
              <td>Number of turns in primary and secondary coils</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>I₁, I₂</strong></td>
              <td>Primary and secondary currents (A)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      
      <p><em>Note:</em> When voltage steps up, current steps down proportionally to conserve power (assuming an ideal transformer).</p>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Step-Up vs. Step-Down Comparison</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Type</th>
              <th>Condition</th>
              <th>Example Use Case</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Step-up</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">N_2 &gt; N_1</span> &rarr; <span class="f">V_2 &gt; V_1</span></td>
              <td>Power transmission stations (high voltage minimizes line losses)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Step-down</strong></td>
              <td><span class="f">N_2 &lt; N_1</span> &rarr; <span class="f">V_2 &lt; V_1</span></td>
              <td>Home appliance adapters, mobile phone chargers</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q4 — Option 1: Interpret step-up and step-down transformers.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>A <strong>transformer</strong> transfers electrical energy from one circuit to another through electromagnetic induction, with a change in voltage level.</p>
          
          <div class="diag-box">
            <div class="dlabel">Single-Phase Transformer Schematic</div>
            <div class="diag-container">
              <img class="diagram-img" src="images/transformer_core.png" alt="Transformer Construction Schematic">
            </div>
            <div class="ddesc">Transformer with laminated core, primary coil N₁ turns on left, secondary coil N₂ turns on right, input V₁ on primary side, output V₂ on secondary side.</div>
          </div>

          <p>The governing equation is:</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            <div class="flabel">Transformation Ratio</div>
            <span class="formula-line">V_1 / V_2 = N_1 / N_2 = I_2 / I_1</span>
          </div>
          <p>where <span class="f">N₁, N₂</span> = number of turns; <span class="f">V₁, V₂</span> = voltages; <span class="f">I₁, I₂</span> = currents.</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Step-Up Transformer:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">N_2 &gt; N_1</span>, so <span class="f">V_2 &gt; V_1</span>. It increases the voltage from primary to secondary. Current on the secondary side decreases proportionally (since power is conserved: <span class="f">V_1 I_1 = V_2 I_2</span>). Used in power transmission lines where high voltage is needed to reduce current and minimize losses.</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Step-Down Transformer:</strong><br>
          <span class="f">N_1 &gt; N_2</span>, so <span class="f">V_2 &lt; V_1</span>. It decreases the voltage. Current on the secondary side increases. Used in household distribution to step 11kV or 33kV down to 230V for home use.</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;">In both cases, power is ideally conserved (ignoring losses): Input VA = Output VA.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Why a Transformer Fails on DC</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Core Concept Reason</div>
        <p>DC produces a <strong>constant (steady) current</strong>. A constant current creates a <strong>constant magnetic flux</strong> — it does not change with time.</p>
        <p style="margin-top: 6px;">Since there is <strong>no change in flux</strong> (<span class="f">d&Phi;/dt = 0</span>), there is <strong>no induced EMF</strong> in the secondary winding according to Faraday's Law. The transformer simply fails to function.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Overheating Danger:</strong> On DC, the primary winding has no inductive reactance (<span class="f">X_L = 0</span>) and behaves like a pure low resistor. If a standard DC supply is connected, the primary will draw an extremely large current, overheat, and burn out the winding.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST1</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q4 — Option 2: Why does a transformer fail to operate on DC?
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>A transformer is designed exclusively for AC. When DC is applied, it fails to function and may actually be damaged. Here is why:</p>
          <p><strong>1. Transformer operates on Faraday's law:</strong><br>
          The induced EMF in the secondary coil is <span class="f">e = &minus;N d&Phi;/dt</span>. An EMF is only induced when the magnetic flux is changing (<span class="f">d&Phi;/dt &ne; 0</span>).</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. DC produces constant flux:</strong><br>
          Direct current is steady. A steady current in the primary creates a constant magnetic flux in the core. Since flux is not changing, <span class="f">d&Phi;/dt = 0</span>, so no EMF is induced in the secondary. Energy transfer fails completely.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>3. No back EMF in primary:</strong><br>
          In AC operation, the changing flux induces a back EMF in the primary that limits the current. With DC, there is no changing flux, so no back EMF is generated.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>4. Primary acts as a low-resistance wire:</strong><br>
          The DC resistance of the primary winding is very small (just the winding's copper resistance, typically a few ohms). Without back EMF, an extremely large current flows through the primary.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>5. Result — overheating and failure:</strong><br>
          This massive current causes severe <span class="f">I&sup2;R</span> heating, burns the insulation, and destroys the winding within seconds.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>In short:</strong> A transformer needs a changing flux to function — and only AC can create that. DC gives constant flux, zero output, and a burnt primary coil.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">🌀</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 3 — 3-Phase Induction Motor (IM)</strong><br>
      The industry workhorse. Powered by a rotating magnetic field in the stator, the rotor revolves slightly below synchronous speed to sustain induction torque.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Working Principle &amp; Slip</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>A 3-phase induction motor converts three-phase AC electrical energy into mechanical rotation. The rotor is not electrically connected to the supply — it gets its energy purely through induction (similar to a transformer secondary).</p>
      
      <div class="sub-section-title">Step-by-Step Working</div>
      <ol>
        <li>Three-phase AC supply is applied to the stator windings.</li>
        <li>This creates a <strong>Rotating Magnetic Field (RMF)</strong> that physically rotates at synchronous speed.</li>
        <li>The rotating field cuts across the rotor conductors, inducing an EMF (Faraday's Law).</li>
        <li>The induced EMF drives a current through the short-circuited rotor conductors.</li>
        <li>This current-carrying rotor sits inside the stator magnetic field, producing a force (Lorentz force / Fleming's Left Hand Rule).</li>
        <li>The rotor begins to rotate in the direction of the rotating field.</li>
      </ol>
      
      <div class="note">
        <strong>The Speed Difference:</strong> The rotor must rotate <strong>slightly slower</strong> than the rotating stator field. If they ran at the exact same speed, there would be no relative motion, zero induced EMF, and zero torque.
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Synchronous Speed</div>
      <p>The speed of the rotating magnetic field is called <strong>synchronous speed</strong> (<span class="f">N_s</span>):</p>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Synchronous Speed Equation</div>
        <span class="formula-line">N_s = 120 * f / P  (RPM)</span>
      </div>
      <p>Where <span class="f">f</span> is supply frequency (typically 50 Hz in India) and <span class="f">P</span> is the number of poles.</p>
      
      <p><strong>Common Pole Configurations at 50 Hz:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>4 Poles &rarr; <span class="f">Ns = (120 &times; 50) / 4 = 1500 RPM</span></li>
        <li>6 Poles &rarr; <span class="f">Ns = (120 &times; 50) / 6 = 1000 RPM</span></li>
        <li>8 Poles &rarr; <span class="f">Ns = (120 &times; 50) / 8 = 750 RPM</span></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Fractional &amp; Percentage Slip</div>
      <p>The rotor speed (<span class="f">N</span>) lags the synchronous speed. The difference is expressed as <strong>slip</strong> (<span class="f">s</span>):</p>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="flabel">Slip Equations</div>
        <span class="formula-line">Fractional Slip: s = (N_s - N) / N_s</span>
        <span class="formula-line">Percentage Slip: s% = [ (N_s - N) / N_s ] * 100</span>
      </div>
      
      <ul>
        <li><strong>At Standstill (start):</strong> <span class="f">N = 0</span> &rarr; <span class="f">s = 1</span> (100% slip).</li>
        <li><strong>At Synchronous Speed:</strong> <span class="f">N = N_s</span> &rarr; <span class="f">s = 0</span> (impossible under normal running).</li>
        <li><strong>Normal Operation:</strong> Slip is typically between <strong>3% and 8%</strong>.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.1(a) A 3-phase induction motor has 26 poles and is connected to 50 Hz AC supply. Find the synchronous speed of the RMF in the motor.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>The synchronous speed formula is:</p>
          <div class="formula-box" style="margin: 8px 0;">
            <span class="formula-line">N_s = 120 * f / P</span>
          </div>
          <p>Where:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><span class="f">f</span> = supply frequency = 50 Hz</li>
            <li><span class="f">P</span> = number of poles = 26</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Substituting the values:</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 4px;"><span class="f">N_s = (120 &times; 50) / 26 = 6000 / 26 ≈ <strong>230.77 RPM</strong></span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Torque-Slip Characteristic Curve</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>This curve demonstrates how the torque produced by the induction motor changes as slip goes from standstill (<span class="f">s=1</span>) to synchronous speed (<span class="f">s=0</span>).</p>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — Torque-Slip Characteristics</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/torque_slip_curve.png" alt="Torque-Slip Characteristics Curve">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Plot Torque (Y-axis) vs. Slip (X-axis, from 0 to 1). The curve rises from 0 at s=0 to a peak (T_max) at s_mt (~20%), then drops to a moderate T_st at s=1. Shade stable and unstable regions.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=3+phase+induction+motor+torque+slip+characteristic+curve+stable+unstable+zone&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: Torque-Slip Curve</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Analysis of Zones</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Operating Point / Zone</th>
              <th>Slip Value</th>
              <th>Behaviour Description</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>s = 1 (Standstill)</strong></td>
              <td>100%</td>
              <td>Rotor speed N = 0. Torque produced here is starting torque (<span class="f">T_st</span>).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Breakdown Torque</strong></td>
              <td>s ≈ 20% – 25%</td>
              <td>Torque reaches its absolute maximum peak (<span class="f">T_max</span>). If loaded beyond this, motor stalls.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Stable Region</strong></td>
              <td>s = 0 to s_mt (Low Slip)</td>
              <td>Normal operating region. As load increases, slip increases slightly, and torque increases to match it.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Unstable Region</strong></td>
              <td>s = s_mt to 1 (High Slip)</td>
              <td>If motor enters this region under load, it cannot sustain speed and will quickly decelerate to a halt.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="note" style="margin-top: 14px;">
        <strong>Why the curve has a peak:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>At low slip (close to s=0), rotor frequency is low, so rotor resistance dominates. Torque is proportional to slip.</li>
          <li>At high slip (close to s=1), rotor frequency is high, so rotor leakage reactance dominates. Torque is inversely proportional to slip.</li>
          <li>The peak is the boundary where resistance and reactance effects balance.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.4 Interpret the torque-slip curve of a three-phase induction motor and explain its significance.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/induction_motor_torque_solved.png" alt="Torque-Slip Curve of 3-Phase Induction Motor" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>

          <p><strong>1. What Slip Is:</strong></p>
          <p>Slip is the difference between synchronous speed (<span class="f">N_s</span>) and actual rotor speed (<span class="f">N</span>), expressed as a fraction:</p>
          <div class="formula-box" style="margin: 8px 0;">
            <span class="formula-line">s = (N_s - N) / N_s</span>
          </div>
          <p>At standstill (<span class="f">N = 0</span>), <span class="f">s = 1</span>. At synchronous speed (<span class="f">N = N_s</span>), <span class="f">s = 0</span> (which never actually happens in a loaded motor).</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Low Slip Region (Normal Operating Zone — s = 0 to s_mt):</strong></p>
          <p>In this region, torque is nearly proportional to slip. As load increases slightly, rotor slows just a bit, slip increases slightly, and torque rises to match the load. This is the <strong>stable operating region</strong> — the motor self-corrects when load changes.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>3. Maximum Torque — Breakdown Torque:</strong></p>
          <p>As slip increases beyond a critical value, torque reaches its peak called <strong>breakdown torque</strong> or maximum torque (<span class="f">T_max</span>). This is the highest torque the motor can deliver without stalling. If load exceeds this, the motor cannot recover.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>4. High Slip Region (s = breakdown slip s_mt to 1):</strong></p>
          <p>Beyond the breakdown point, torque actually decreases as slip increases. This is the <strong>unstable region</strong> — if the motor enters here, it will stall completely (<span class="f">s &rarr; 1</span>) unless the load is reduced. Normal operation never occurs here.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>5. Significance of the Curve:</strong></p>
          <p>The torque-slip curve tells us the starting torque (at <span class="f">s=1</span>), the safe operating range, the maximum load capacity, and where the motor is stable. Engineers use this to select the right motor for a given load and to design starting methods for heavy-load applications.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">⚙️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 3 — DC Motor Construction &amp; Principles</strong><br>
      A DC motor converts direct current electrical energy into mechanical rotation, relying on Lorentz force and commutator rectifying action.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Working Principle &amp; Construction</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>A DC motor converts direct current (DC) electrical energy into mechanical rotation. It works on the principle that <strong>a current-carrying conductor placed inside a magnetic field experiences a mechanical force</strong> (Lorentz force).</p>
      
      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Fleming's Left-Hand Rule (Force Direction)</div>
        <p>Align your thumb, index finger, and middle finger perpendicular to each other:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Index Finger:</strong> Point in the direction of the Magnetic Field (N &rarr; S).</li>
          <li><strong>Middle Finger:</strong> Point in the direction of the Current (I).</li>
          <li><strong>Thumb:</strong> Points in the direction of the resulting Force/Motion.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — DC Motor Cross-Sectional Diagram</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/dc_motor_cross.png" alt="2-Pole DC Motor Cross-Sectional Diagram">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw circular yoke outline, internal magnetic poles (labeled N and S), armature core in the center, and coils inside slot marks. Show brushes resting on the commutator.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=DC+motor+constructional+cross+section+labeled+yoke+armature+brushes+poles&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: DC Motor Construction</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">DC Motor Components &amp; Functions</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Component</th>
              <th>Functional Description</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Yoke</strong></td>
              <td>The outer cylindrical frame (cast iron/steel). Provides mechanical support and serves as the magnetic return path.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Field Poles</strong></td>
              <td>Projecting iron pole pieces inside the yoke. Creates the main magnetic path inside the machine.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Field Winding</strong></td>
              <td>Copper coils wound around poles. Carrying current here excites and produces the stator magnetic field.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Armature Core</strong></td>
              <td>Laminated iron cylinder with slot grooves. Houses armature winding conductors and rotates.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Armature Winding</strong></td>
              <td>Coils in armature core slots. Carrying current here experiences the physical torque force.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Commutator</strong></td>
              <td>Segmented copper cylinder on the shaft. Converts alternating current inside the armature to unidirectional (DC) current in the external circuit — acts as a mechanical rectifier.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Brushes</strong></td>
              <td>Stationary carbon blocks pressing on the commutator. Ensures electrical contact between rotating armature and stationary external terminals.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Air Gap</strong></td>
              <td>Symmetric gap separating stator poles and rotor armature. Magnetic flux passes across this space.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.4 (OR) Compare the functions of different components used in the construction of a DC motor with the help of a diagram.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/dc_motor_construction_solved.png" alt="Constructional Details of a DC Motor" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>

          <p><strong>1. Yoke (Outer Frame):</strong></p>
          <p>The <strong>yoke</strong> is the outer cylindrical steel body. It provides mechanical support to the entire motor and also acts as the magnetic return path for the flux produced by the field poles. It must be made of material with high magnetic permeability.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Field Poles and Field Winding:</strong></p>
          <p>The <strong>field poles</strong> are projecting electromagnets fixed to the yoke. They carry the <strong>field winding</strong> (coils of wire) which, when energised with DC, produces the main magnetic flux in the motor. This flux is what the armature conductors cut to produce torque.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>3. Armature Core and Armature Winding:</strong></p>
          <p>The <strong>armature</strong> is the rotating part. Its core is made of laminated silicon steel to reduce eddy current losses. The <strong>armature winding</strong> sits in slots cut into this core — these are the conductors that carry current and interact with the field flux to produce mechanical force (torque).</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>4. Commutator:</strong></p>
          <p>The <strong>commutator</strong> is a cylindrical assembly of copper segments mounted on the shaft, insulated from each other. It reverses the direction of current in the armature conductors every half rotation, ensuring that the torque always acts in the same direction — making continuous rotation possible.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>5. Brushes:</strong></p>
          <p><strong>Carbon brushes</strong> press against the rotating commutator and maintain electrical contact between the stationary supply circuit and the rotating armature winding. They are made of carbon to reduce wear and have good electrical conductivity. Without brushes, current cannot reach the armature.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Types of DC Motors</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>Depending on how the field winding and armature winding are electrically interconnected, DC motors are classified into three types:</p>

      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Type</th>
              <th>Connection Details</th>
              <th>Operational Characteristics &amp; Applications</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Series Motor</strong></td>
              <td>Field winding is connected in <strong>series</strong> with armature winding.</td>
              <td>Extremely high starting torque. Speed decreases dramatically as load increases. <strong>Never start a series motor at zero load</strong> (it can run away to dangerously high speed). Used in traction, electric trains, cranes.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Shunt Motor</strong></td>
              <td>Field winding is connected in <strong>parallel (shunt)</strong> with armature winding.</td>
              <td>Nearly constant operating speed. Speed varies only slightly from no-load to full-load. Ideal for constant speed machinery: lathes, fans, centrifugal pumps.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Compound Motor</strong></td>
              <td>Features both a <strong>series field</strong> and a <strong>shunt field</strong>.</td>
              <td>Combines the constant-speed properties of shunt and the starting-torque advantages of series. Used in heavy punch presses, elevators.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ==================== TAB: MODULE 4 ==================== -->
<div id="m4" class="panel">
  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">🔌</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 4 — Electrical Installations: Wires &amp; Cables</strong><br>
      Understand conductors, cable structures, insulation materials like PVC/XLPE, and armoured cable details for safe electrical distribution.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Wires vs. Cables (Basic Difference)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>A <strong>wire</strong> is a single electrical conductor, typically made of copper or aluminium, which may or may not be insulated. A <strong>cable</strong> consists of two or more insulated wires bundled together inside a common protective outer sheath.</p>
      
      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Why Cables are Used in Installations</div>
        <p>Cables allow multiple conductors (e.g., Live, Neutral, and Earth) to be routed together securely in a single package. The outer protective sheath shielding the inner wires provides critical mechanical protection, prevents short circuits, and guards against moisture/corrosive environments.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Types of Wires and Cables</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>Electrical installations employ different cables depending on load current, environment temperature, and mechanical hazard levels:</p>

      <div class="sub-section-title">1. PVC (Polyvinyl Chloride) Cable</div>
      <p>This is the most common type used in low-voltage domestic wiring. The conductors are insulated with a layer of PVC plastic.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Domestic light points, switches, ceiling fans, and socket wiring.</li>
        <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Cheap, highly flexible, easy to strip and run, and chemically resistant to moisture.</li>
        <li><strong>Limitation:</strong> PVC cannot handle very high temperatures. The insulation starts to soften and melt above <strong>70°C</strong>.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.1(c) What is the role of PVC coating in electrical wires?
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>The role of PVC (Polyvinyl Chloride) coating in electrical wires includes:</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <li><strong>Electrical Insulation:</strong> Since PVC is a non-conductive polymer with high dielectric strength, it prevents leakage current and protects humans from electric shocks when touching active wires.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>Environmental & Mechanical Protection:</strong> Shields the copper or aluminium core from moisture, chemical corrosion, dust, oxidation, and direct physical abrasion.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">2. XLPE (Cross-Linked Polyethylene) Cable</div>
      <p>In XLPE cables, the polyethylene insulation undergoes a chemical "cross-linking" treatment. This process changes the molecular structure, forming links between polymer chains that greatly increase heat resistance.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Industrial power distribution, underground feeders, and high-load circuits.</li>
        <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Can handle continuous operating temperatures up to <strong>90°C</strong> (and up to 250°C under short-circuit conditions). It has superior electrical properties, higher current-carrying capacity, and a longer lifespan than PVC.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="sub-section-title">3. Armoured Cable (Steel Wire Armoured — SWA)</div>
      <p>This cable contains one or more copper conductors wrapped in insulation, surrounded by a protective layer of steel wires or steel tape (the armour), which is then covered by an outer plastic sheath.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Underground power mains, industrial switchyards, outdoor lighting, and environments with high mechanical hazard risks.</li>
        <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Extremely high resistance to physical damage (crushing, falling tools, rodent bites, or excavation tools). The steel armour layer must always be connected to the earth wire for additional safety.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="sub-section-title">4. Flexible Cable (Flex)</div>
      <p>Unlike solid wires that use a single solid metal core, flexible cables use many extremely fine copper strands twisted together into a single conductor.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Appliance supply cords (irons, kettles, mixers), extension leads, and portable industrial tools.</li>
        <li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Can bend and flex repeatedly without metal fatigue or breaking.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Conductor Materials Comparison</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Material</th>
              <th>Key Properties</th>
              <th>Primary Applications</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Copper (Cu)</strong></td>
              <td>Very high electrical conductivity, highly flexible, low corrosion rate, but expensive.</td>
              <td>Almost all domestic, commercial, and appliance internal wiring.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Aluminium (Al)</strong></td>
              <td>Lighter weight, much cheaper, but has only 60% of copper's conductivity and is more brittle.</td>
              <td>Overhead power transmission lines, long-distance distribution feeders.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Exam Point (MST2 Recall):</strong> PVC coating on electrical conductors serves two main purposes: **electrical insulation** (prevents shocks and short-circuits) and **environmental protection** (shields the metal conductor from moisture, oxidation, and corrosion).
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.1(b) List the different types of cable and wires with the help of neat sketches.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/cable_types.png" alt="Cross sections of different cable types" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>
          <p>Types: <strong>Solid wire</strong>, <strong>Stranded wire</strong>, <strong>Coaxial cable</strong>, <strong>Twisted pair cable</strong>, and <strong>Armoured cable (SWA)</strong>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.5(a) Explain wires and cables in detail.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>1. Solid (Single-Core) Wire:</strong></p>
          <p>A solid wire consists of one thick conductor (copper or aluminium) with a PVC insulation coat. Rigid and maintains its shape. Used in fixed household wiring inside walls and conduits — where the wire will never need to flex. Easy to terminate and connect. The PVC insulation prevents contact between conductors and prevents short circuits.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Stranded Wire:</strong></p>
          <p>Made of multiple thin conductors twisted together and covered with PVC insulation. The twisting gives <strong>flexibility</strong> — the wire can bend repeatedly without breaking. Used in appliance cords, flexible connections inside control panels, automotive wiring, and any application where the wire moves during service.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>3. Twin-Core and Multi-Core Cables:</strong></p>
          <p>Multiple individually insulated cores are bundled inside a common outer sheath. A twin-core cable has a live and neutral. A 3-core cable adds an earth conductor. The colour coding (Brown = Live, Blue = Neutral, Green-Yellow = Earth per IEC 60446) identifies each core. Used for fixed domestic wiring, connecting switches, sockets, and appliances.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>4. Coaxial Cable:</strong></p>
          <p>Has a centre conductor, surrounded by solid or foam insulation, then a braided or foil metallic shield, and an outer PVC jacket. The shield blocks external electromagnetic interference from reaching the centre conductor and also prevents the signal inside from radiating out. Used for cable TV, antenna connections, and RF signal transmission.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>5. Armoured Cable (SWA — Steel Wire Armoured):</strong></p>
          <p>Has conductors insulated individually, then bundled inside an inner sheath, then wrapped with a layer of <strong>galvanised steel wires</strong>, and finally an outer PVC jacket. The steel armour provides mechanical protection against crushing, rodent attack, and accidental digging. Used for underground power distribution, outdoor installations, and industrial power supply.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">🛡️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 4 — Protective Devices: MCB &amp; ELCB</strong><br>
      Explore reusable circuit protection. MCBs safeguard cables from overloads and shorts, while ELCBs/RCCBs protect human lives from electrical leakage.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. MCB (Miniature Circuit Breaker)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>An MCB is an electromagnetic safety switch designed to **automatically open the circuit** when current exceeds safe limits. It can be easily reset manually after clearing the fault, making it far superior to traditional fuses that must be replaced.</p>
      
      <div class="sub-section-title">Why choose MCB over a fuse?</div>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Resettable:</strong> Eliminates the hassle of rewiring fuse elements.</li>
        <li><strong>Precision &amp; Speed:</strong> Trips faster and operates at exact current thresholds.</li>
        <li><strong>Safety:</strong> Provides separate thermal and magnetic tripping, ensuring safer handling for the user.</li>
        <li><strong>Fault Diagnosis:</strong> The switch toggle clearly jumps to the OFF/tripped position, indicating which circuit has faulted.</li>
      </ol>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.1(c) What is difference between fuse and circuit breaker?
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>A <strong>fuse</strong> is a one-time protection device — once it blows due to overcurrent, it must be replaced entirely. A <strong>circuit breaker</strong> (like an MCB) is reusable — it trips and can be reset by flipping the switch. A fuse is cheaper but a circuit breaker is more convenient and reliable for repeated use.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.1(b) State the primary functions of a Miniature Circuit Breaker (MCB).
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>The primary functions of an MCB are:</p>
          <ol style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <li><strong>Overload Protection (Thermal):</strong> Employs a bimetallic strip that heats up and bends over a period of time during sustained moderate overcurrents, releasing a latch to trip the contacts.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>Short Circuit Protection (Magnetic):</strong> Uses an electromagnetic solenoid that instantly pulls a plunger under massive current surges, tripping the contacts within milliseconds to safeguard wiring and equipment.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Internal Construction &amp; Tripping Mechanisms</div>
      <p>An MCB incorporates two separate tripping mechanisms inside its insulated housing:</p>
      
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bimetallic Strip (Thermal Trip - Overload Protection):</strong>
          Consists of two different metal strips bonded together. When a sustained overload current flows, heat builds up, causing the metals to expand at different rates. The strip bends, releasing a mechanical latch that forces the main contacts open. This response is relatively slow (seconds to minutes).
        </li>
        <li><strong>Solenoid Coil &amp; Plunger (Magnetic Trip - Short Circuit Protection):</strong>
          An electromagnet coil wrapped around an iron plunger. Under normal current, the magnetic pull is negligible. During a short circuit, the current spikes instantly to massive levels. This creates an extremely strong magnetic force that pulls the plunger, instantly releasing the trip latch and opening the contacts in milliseconds.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Arc Chute (Arc Suppressor):</strong>
          When the contacts open under high current, a hot electrical spark (arc) forms between them. The arc chute is a series of parallel metal splitter plates that draws the arc in, breaks it into tiny segments, cools it, and extinguishes it safely.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Trip Mechanism &amp; Toggle Switch:</strong>
          The external toggle handle provides manual ON/OFF control and is linked internally to the latch. The latch holds the spring-loaded contacts closed until released by either the bimetallic strip or the solenoid plunger.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — MCB Schematic Internal Diagram</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/mcb_schematic.png" alt="MCB Schematic Diagram">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw a block schematic including input/output terminals, solenoid coil with plunger, bimetallic strip showing bending direction, operating latch with toggle handle, contacts, and arc chute splitter plates.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=miniature+circuit+breaker+internal+construction+parts+diagram&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: MCB Internal Diagram</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Working — Three Operating States</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Condition</th>
              <th>Current level</th>
              <th>Active Component</th>
              <th>Resulting Action</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Normal</strong></td>
              <td>&le; Rated Current</td>
              <td>None</td>
              <td>Thermal and magnetic forces are too weak to trip the latch. Contacts remain closed.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Overload</strong></td>
              <td>Moderate excess (e.g., 1.5x)</td>
              <td>Bimetallic Strip</td>
              <td>Strip heats up slowly, bends over a few seconds/minutes, releases latch. Contacts open.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Short Circuit</strong></td>
              <td>Massive spike (e.g., &gt;10x)</td>
              <td>Solenoid Coil</td>
              <td>Coil creates strong electromagnet pull, instantly pulls plunger, opens contacts in milliseconds. Arc chute extinguishes spark.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Important Protection Limit:</strong> MCB protects wires and equipment from thermal damage due to overcurrents and short circuits. It **does not** detect leakage currents to ground or protect humans from direct electric shocks. That requires an ELCB.
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.2 Explain the construction and working of a Miniature Circuit Breaker (MCB) with a neat diagram.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/mcb_construction_solved.png" alt="Internal Construction of an MCB" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>

          <p><strong>1. Main Construction Components:</strong></p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <li><strong>Insulated Housing:</strong> A durable, heat-resistant plastic outer casing that encloses all components.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 4px;"><strong>Bimetallic Strip:</strong> Provides thermal overload protection. Made of two metals with different expansion rates.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 4px;"><strong>Solenoid Coil &amp; Plunger:</strong> Provides magnetic short-circuit protection. Creates a rapid magnetic field during high currents.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 4px;"><strong>Trip Latch &amp; Operating Mechanism:</strong> The mechanical spring-loaded system that forces contacts open when triggered.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 4px;"><strong>Arc Chute:</strong> A stacked assembly of metal splitter plates that splits, cools, and extinguishes the electrical spark (arc) formed during contact separation.</li>
          </ul>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Working Principle — Two Tripping Methods:</strong></p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <li><strong>Thermal Overload Working:</strong> Under moderate prolonged excess current (overload), the bimetallic strip heats up and slowly bends. The physical bending eventually releases the trip latch, causing the main contacts to fly open. This is a slow, time-delayed action.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>Magnetic Short Circuit Working:</strong> Under heavy, instantaneous currents (short circuit), a high current surge passes through the solenoid coil. This generates a very strong magnetic field that instantly pulls the iron plunger down. The plunger physically hits the trip latch, releasing it immediately to open the contacts in under 10 milliseconds.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. ELCB (Earth Leakage Circuit Breaker)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>An ELCB (also commonly called an RCCB — Residual Current Circuit Breaker) is a life-saving device that detects **electric current leaking to ground** and instantly disconnects the supply. It is designed to prevent fatal electrocutions.</p>
      
      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Why ELCB is Critical for Human Safety</div>
        <p>A normal fuse or MCB will only trip if current exceeds ratings (e.g., 16 A, 32 A). However, a current of just **30 mA to 50 mA** flowing through the human body is enough to paralyze the heart and cause death. An ELCB is designed to trip when leakage current reaches **30 mA**, acting in less than **30 milliseconds** to save lives.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Construction details</div>
      <p>The core of an ELCB/RCCB is a <strong>Core Balance Current Transformer (CBCT)</strong>, which consists of:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Toroidal Core:</strong> A ring-shaped magnetic core made of high-permeability iron.</li>
        <li><strong>Primary Windings:</strong> The Live and Neutral conductors of the circuit are wound in opposite directions through the center of the ring.</li>
        <li><strong>Secondary Winding (Sensing Winding):</strong> A separate sensing coil wound around the toroidal ring.</li>
        <li><strong>Trip Coil &amp; Relay Latch:</strong> Connected to the secondary winding. It triggers the main contacts to spring open when energized.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — ELCB / RCCB Working Circuit Diagram</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/elcb_schematic.png" alt="ELCB / RCCB Circuit Diagram">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw Live and Neutral lines passing through a toroidal CBCT core to a load. Draw a secondary winding on the core feeding a trip coil. Show a fault path to ground representing leakage.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=earth+leakage+circuit+breaker+working+principle+circuit+diagram&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: ELCB Working Diagram</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Working Principle — Normal vs. Fault Conditions</div>
      
      <p><strong>1. Normal Condition (Balanced Currents):</strong></p>
      <p>All current entering the load via the Live wire (<span class="f">I_L</span>) returns via the Neutral wire (<span class="f">I_N</span>). Thus, <span class="f">I_L = I_N</span>. Since the Live and Neutral lines are wound in opposite directions, their magnetic fluxes inside the toroidal core are equal and opposite, canceling each other out. Net flux <span class="f">&Phi; = 0</span>. No EMF is induced in the secondary winding. The trip coil remains unenergized, and the contacts stay closed.</p>
      
      <p><strong>2. Fault Condition (Leakage to Earth):</strong></p>
      <p>If an insulation failure occurs and a person touches the metallic casing of a faulty appliance, some current leaks through the person to the earth. Now, the return current in the Neutral wire is less than the current in the Live wire (<span class="f">I_L &gt; I_N</span>). The magnetic fluxes inside the core no longer cancel, leaving a net residual flux (<span class="f">&Phi; &ne; 0</span>). This changing residual flux induces an EMF in the secondary winding. The induced voltage energizes the trip coil, which releases the latch and trips the main contacts instantly (within 30 ms).</p>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.5(c) With a neat labeled diagram, explain the construction and working of ELCB. Differentiate normal and fault conditions.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/elcb_construction_solved.png" alt="Working Diagram of ELCB" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>

          <p><strong>Construction:</strong></p>
          <p>The core of an Earth Leakage Circuit Breaker (ELCB / RCCB) is a Core Balance Current Transformer (CBCT). It consists of a high-permeability toroidal iron ring. Both the Live and Neutral wires from the supply pass through the center of this ring in opposite directions, acting as primary windings. A secondary sensing coil is wound around the ring and connected to an electromagnetic trip relay.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Working Principle:</strong></p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong>1. Normal Condition:</strong></p>
          <p>During normal operation, the current flowing to the load via the Live wire is exactly equal to the current returning via the Neutral wire (<span class="f">I_L = I_N</span>). Since they flow in opposite directions, the magnetic flux produced by the Live wire is perfectly cancelled by the flux produced by the Neutral wire. The net magnetic flux in the toroidal core is zero (<span class="f">&Phi; = 0</span>). No voltage is induced in the secondary coil, and the trip relay remains inactive.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong>2. Fault Condition (Earth Leakage):</strong></p>
          <p>If an insulation fault occurs and leakage current flows to the earth (e.g., through a person touching a live metallic casing), the return current in the Neutral wire becomes less than the Live wire current (<span class="f">I_L &gt; I_N</span>). This imbalance creates a net residual magnetic flux in the toroidal core. The changing flux induces an alternating EMF in the secondary sensing coil. If the leakage reaches the threshold (usually 30 mA), the induced voltage energizes the trip relay, which pulls the mechanical latch and opens the main contacts in less than 30 ms, disconnecting the supply and saving the person from electrocution.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">3. Protective Devices Comparison (MCB vs. ELCB vs. MCCB)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body">
      <div class="cmp-container">
