        </table>
      </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.1(b) Which breaker can handle higher current capacities, MCB or MCCB?
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>MCCB (Moulded Case Circuit Breaker)</strong> handles much higher current capacities. An MCB is rated up to about <strong>125A</strong> and is used in domestic and small commercial circuits. An MCCB is rated from <strong>100A up to 2500A</strong> and is used in industrial panels, large commercial buildings, and distribution boards where high fault currents must be interrupted.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.3 Explain any two out of MCB, ELCB and MCCB.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p><strong>— MCB (Miniature Circuit Breaker) —</strong></p>
          <p><strong>1. What MCB Does:</strong> An MCB automatically disconnects a circuit during overload or short circuit and can be manually reset — no fuse replacement needed. Rated for currents up to about 125A.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>2. Construction and Working:</strong> It has two internal protective elements: a <strong>bimetallic strip</strong> (for overloads) and an <strong>electromagnetic solenoid</strong> (for short circuits). Under sustained overload, the bimetallic strip heats, bends, and trips the mechanism. Under a sudden short circuit, the massive current creates a strong magnetic field in the solenoid that instantly snaps the contacts open. An <strong>arc chute</strong> suppresses the arc.</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 12px;"><strong>— ELCB (Earth Leakage Circuit Breaker) —</strong></p>
          <p><strong>3. What ELCB Does:</strong> An ELCB detects current leaking to earth (as small as 30mA) and disconnects the supply within 30–40ms. This protects humans from electrocution.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>4. Working Principle:</strong> Both live and neutral wires pass through a toroidal magnetic core. Under normal conditions, live current equals return neutral current — their fluxes cancel. When fault current leaks to earth, live current exceeds neutral current. The net residual flux induces a voltage in the sensing coil, which triggers the relay and opens the trip contacts.</p>
          
          <p style="margin-top: 12px;"><strong>5. Key Difference:</strong> MCB protects equipment and wiring from overloads and short circuits (reacts to high currents). ELCB protects people from electrocution by detecting earth leakage currents.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">🕳️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 4 — Earthing Systems: Pipe Earthing</strong><br>
      Explore the construction, moisture retention, and dimensions of Pipe Earthing. Learn how to achieve a low-resistance path to zero potential.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Concept of Earthing &amp; Its Need</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p><strong>Earthing</strong> (or Grounding) is the process of connecting the metallic enclosure or non-current carrying metal parts of an electrical appliance to the deep earth mass via a highly conducting wire. The Earth is considered to be a massive conductor at <strong>zero electrical potential</strong>.</p>
      
      <div class="sub-section-title">Why Earthing is Critical</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Preventing Shock:</strong> Under normal conditions, metal enclosures are isolated from live terminals. If insulation fails and the live wire touches the metal casing, the casing becomes live at 230 V. If a person touches it, current flows through their body to ground, causing a severe shock. With earthing, the metal casing is connected to a low-resistance path, so the fault current flows safely to ground, bypassing the person.</li>
        <li><strong>Triggering Breakers:</strong> The sudden rush of heavy fault current down the earthing path instantly exceeds the MCB/fuse rating, causing the MCB to trip and isolating the faulty circuit immediately.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Pipe Earthing Construction &amp; Materials</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>Pipe earthing is the most common and effective earthing method, preferred in sandy or rocky soils. It uses a vertically buried **GI (Galvanised Iron) pipe** as the earth electrode.</p>
      
      <div class="sub-section-title">Construction details &amp; Dimensions</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>GI Pipe (Electrode):</strong> Must have a minimum diameter of **38 mm** and a minimum length of **2.5 metres**. Holes (perforations) are drilled along its length to allow moisture and ions to diffuse easily.</li>
        <li><strong>Charcoal Layer:</strong> A 15 cm thick layer of charcoal is packed surrounding the GI pipe in the pit. Charcoal absorbs and retains moisture in the soil, keeping earth resistance low during dry seasons.</li>
        <li><strong>Salt Layer:</strong> Alternating with charcoal, common salt (sodium chloride) is added. Salt dissolves in moisture to release ions, dramatically increasing the electrical conductivity of the surrounding soil.</li>
        <li><strong>Funnel with Wire Mesh:</strong> Placed at the top of the pipe above the ground level. Periodic pouring of water down the funnel keeps the charcoal-salt mixture moist. The wire mesh prevents debris or soil from entering and blocking the pipe.</li>
        <li><strong>GI Earth Wire:</strong> A solid GI wire is connected securely to the pipe using nuts/bolts and run to the main distribution board earth terminal.</li>
        <li><strong>Concrete Chamber:</strong> A brick masonry or concrete inspection chamber with a Cast Iron (CI) cover is built at the top for maintenance access.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — Pipe Earthing Pit Sectional Diagram</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/pipe_earthing_pit.png" alt="Pipe Earthing Pit Sectional Diagram">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw ground level, concrete chamber with CI cover, funnel with wire mesh, GI pipe showing perforations, surrounding layers of salt &amp; charcoal (15 cm), burial depth (2.5 m), and earth wire.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=pipe+earthing+labeled+diagram+engineering+drawing+dimensions&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: Pipe Earthing Diagram</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Function of Each Component</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Component</th>
              <th>Key Functional Purpose</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>GI Pipe</strong></td>
              <td>Serves as the main earth electrode, providing a low-resistance path to discharge currents deep into the ground.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Charcoal Layer</strong></td>
              <td>Retains moisture in the soil surrounding the electrode. Prevents dry soil from forming a resistive barrier.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Salt (NaCl)</strong></td>
              <td>Dissolves to provide free ions, raising the chemical conductivity of the soil and lowering earth resistance.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Watering Funnel</strong></td>
              <td>Allows manual water addition during dry seasons to maintain moisture levels.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Wire Mesh</strong></td>
              <td>Filters out dirt and blockages during watering.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Perforations</strong></td>
              <td>Holes in the GI pipe that let water and dissolved ions pass freely between the pipe interior and surrounding soil.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Earth Resistance Target</strong></td>
              <td>Earth resistance should be kept as low as possible — ideally **less than 1 Ω** for heavy appliances and power stations.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.5(a) Explain the construction of pipe earthing with the help of a neat diagram.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/pipe_earthing_construction_solved.png" alt="Pipe Earthing Construction Pit Diagram" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>

          <p>Pipe earthing is the most common and reliable method of earthing used in domestic and industrial installations. Its construction consists of:</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>1. Earth Electrode (GI Pipe):</strong></p>
          <p>A Galvanised Iron (GI) pipe of minimum <strong>38 mm diameter</strong> and <strong>2.5 metres length</strong> is placed vertically inside a dug earth pit. The pipe has several perforations (holes) drilled along its length to allow moisture to easily enter the surrounding soil.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Moisture Retaining Mixture:</strong></p>
          <p>The empty space around the GI pipe is filled with alternating layers of <strong>Charcoal</strong> and <strong>Salt (NaCl)</strong>, up to a thickness of about 15 cm. The charcoal helps absorb and retain moisture in the soil, while the salt dissolves in the water to provide free ions, dramatically increasing the electrical conductivity (lowering the earth resistance) of the pit.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>3. Watering Arrangement:</strong></p>
          <p>A funnel with a wire mesh is fitted at the top of the GI pipe. In summer or dry seasons, water is poured through this funnel to keep the charcoal-salt mixture wet, ensuring earth resistance remains below 1 ohm.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>4. Connecting Earth Wire:</strong></p>
          <p>A heavy GI earth wire is securely bolted to the top of the pipe (above the funnel) and run to the main distribution board to connect to the metallic casings of equipment.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>5. Inspection Chamber:</strong></p>
          <p>A brick or concrete chamber is built at ground level with a Cast Iron (CI) cover to protect the funnel and the earth wire connection point, and to allow for periodic maintenance and watering.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">3. Section A Preparation — One-Line Q&amp;As</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="green-box">
        <p><strong>Q: What does MCB stand for?</strong><br>
        A: Miniature Circuit Breaker — a protective switch that automatically opens a circuit during overloads and short circuits.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <p><strong>Q: What is the purpose of the bimetallic strip in an MCB?</strong><br>
        A: It provides thermal overload protection. It bends when heated by moderate, prolonged excess current, mechanically releasing the trip latch.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <p><strong>Q: What is an ELCB and what does it detect?</strong><br>
        A: Earth Leakage Circuit Breaker. It detects current leaking to earth by sensing an imbalance between Live and Neutral line currents.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <p><strong>Q: What is the standard trip threshold for an ELCB?</strong><br>
        A: 30 mA leakage current, tripping the circuit in less than 30 milliseconds.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <p><strong>Q: What are the standard dimensions for Pipe Earthing?</strong><br>
        A: A GI pipe of minimum 38 mm diameter, buried vertically at least 2.5 metres deep.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <p><strong>Q: Why are salt and charcoal added in an earthing pit?</strong><br>
        A: Charcoal retains moisture around the electrode, while salt provides ionic conductivity, together minimizing earth resistance.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <p><strong>Q: Why is XLPE preferred over PVC in industrial installations?</strong><br>
        A: XLPE has higher temperature resistance (90°C vs 70°C for PVC), superior mechanical strength, and longer continuous lifespan.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <p><strong>Q: Differentiate between MCB and ELCB targets.</strong><br>
        A: MCB protects electrical wiring and equipment from damage. ELCB protects human life from shock and electrocution.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">4. High-Value Exam Question Formats</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <div class="sub-section-title">5-Mark Question Templates</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Explain the working of MCB with a diagram:</strong>
          Write a definition → List the 2 mechanisms (Bimetallic strip for overload, Solenoid for short circuit) → Briefly explain each mechanism's trigger → Draw the labeled block schematic → State the manual reset advantage over fuses.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Explain Pipe Earthing with a diagram:</strong>
          Define earthing → Detail pit components (GI pipe, funnel, chamber, earth wire) → Draw the labeled cross-sectional diagram with dimensions → Explain the role of charcoal, salt, and periodic watering.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Explain the working of ELCB with a diagram:</strong>
          Define ELCB → Detail construction (CBCT Toroid, primary, secondary windings, trip relay) → Draw circuit schematic → State the 30 mA and 30 ms limits.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="sub-section-title">10-Mark Question Templates</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>With a neat labeled diagram, explain the construction and working of ELCB. Differentiate normal and fault conditions.</strong>
          Define shock hazards and the need for earth leakage detection (2 marks) → Sketch the detailed circuit schematic including Toroidal Core, windings, trip relay, and earth leakage path (4 marks) → Detail Normal Condition (balanced currents <span class="f">I_L = I_N</span>, zero net flux, contacts closed) (2 marks) → Detail Fault Condition (earth leakage path, current imbalance <span class="f">I_L &gt; I_N</span>, net flux inducing secondary EMF, trip coil acts, 30 ms response) (2 marks).
        </li>
        <li><strong>With a neat labeled diagram, explain pipe earthing. State the purpose of each component.</strong>
          Explain shock prevention and zero-potential concept (1 mark) → Draw the full cross-sectional engineering diagram of the 2.5m pit showing Concrete Chamber, CI Cover, Funnel, Mesh, GI Pipe, and layers (5 marks) → List and explain the purpose of the 7 core components (GI pipe, charcoal, salt, funnel, wire mesh, GI wire, pipe holes) (3 marks) → Mention maintenance (watering) and resistance targets (&lt;1 &Omega;) (1 mark).
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ==================== TAB: MODULE 5 ==================== -->
<div id="m5" class="panel">
  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">🌀</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 5 — Transducers: Basic Concepts &amp; Classifications</strong><br>
      Understand how physical physical parameters are converted to electrical signals, the block diagram of a transducer system, and classifications.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. What is a Transducer?</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>A transducer is a device that <strong>converts one form of energy into another</strong>. In electrical and electronics engineering, we specifically care about transducers that convert a <strong>physical quantity</strong> (like displacement, temperature, pressure, force, or flow) into a proportional <strong>electrical signal</strong> (voltage or current) — because electrical signals are easy to measure, transmit, amplify, and process.</p>
      
      <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>A microphone converts sound energy (acoustic pressure waves) into an electrical signal (AC voltage).</li>
        <li>A thermocouple converts thermal energy (heat / temperature difference) into a DC voltage (thermoelectric EMF).</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Exam-Ready Definition</div>
        <p>A transducer is defined as a device which converts a non-electrical physical quantity (measurand) into a proportional electrical signal (such as voltage, current, or electrical impedance).</p>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.1(e) Why do we need a transducer?
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>We need transducers because non-electrical physical quantities (like pressure, temperature, displacement) cannot be easily processed, transmitted, or recorded by electronic control systems. A transducer converts these quantities into proportional electrical signals (voltage/current), which can be easily amplified, transmitted over long distances with minimal loss, digitally processed, and continuously recorded.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Block Diagram of a Transducer System</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>A complete measurement transducer system typically consists of three primary functional blocks: the measurand input, a sensing element, and signal conditioning before producing the final output.</p>
      
      <style>
      .block-diag-container {
        display: flex;
        align-items: center;
        justify-content: space-between;
        gap: 8px;
        margin: 16px 0;
        overflow-x: auto;
        padding: 8px 0;
      }
      .b-box {
        flex: 1;
        min-width: 110px;
        background: #1e293b;
        border: 1px solid #4b5563;
        border-radius: 6px;
        padding: 10px;
        text-align: center;
      }
      .b-box.blue-b { border-color: #3b82f6; background: #0f172a; }
      .b-box.purple-b { border-color: #8b5cf6; background: #1e1b4b; }
      .b-box.orange-b { border-color: #f97316; background: #2c1001; }
      .b-box.green-b-box { border-color: #10b981; background: #022c22; }
      .b-title {
        font-family: 'Sora', sans-serif;
        font-size: 0.85rem;
        font-weight: bold;
        color: #ffffff;
        margin-bottom: 4px;
      }
      .b-desc {
        font-size: 0.75rem;
        color: #9ca3af;
      }
      .b-arrow {
        font-size: 1.2rem;
        color: #6b7280;
        font-weight: bold;
      }
      @media (max-width: 480px) {
        .block-diag-container {
          flex-direction: column;
          gap: 12px;
        }
        .b-arrow {
          transform: rotate(90deg);
        }
        .b-box {
          width: 100%;
        }
      }
      </style>

      <div class="block-diag-container">
        <div class="b-box blue-b">
          <div class="b-title">Physical Quantity</div>
          <div class="b-desc">(Measurand)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="b-arrow">&rarr;</div>
        <div class="b-box purple-b">
          <div class="b-title">Sensing Element</div>
          <div class="b-desc">Primary Transducer</div>
        </div>
        <div class="b-arrow">&rarr;</div>
        <div class="b-box orange-b">
          <div class="b-title">Signal Conditioning</div>
          <div class="b-desc">Secondary Transducer</div>
        </div>
        <div class="b-arrow">&rarr;</div>
        <div class="b-box green-b-box">
          <div class="b-title">Electrical Output</div>
          <div class="b-desc">Voltage / Current</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p><strong>Functions of Each Block:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sensing Element (Primary Transducer):</strong> Directly senses and responds to the physical quantity being measured (measurand). It converts this measurand into a mechanical or physical intermediate signal. <em>(Example: A Bourdon tube senses pressure and converts it into mechanical tip displacement.)</em></li>
        <li><strong>Signal Conditioning (Secondary Transducer):</strong> Takes the intermediate mechanical signal and converts it into a usable electrical signal. <em>(Example: A strain gauge or LVDT senses the displacement of the Bourdon tube and converts it into a resistance or voltage change.)</em></li>
        <li><strong>Electrical Output:</strong> The proportional electrical voltage or current signal which can then be transmitted, displayed on a meter, or fed into a controller/recorder.</li>
      </ul>
      
      <div class="note">
        <strong>Design Note:</strong> Some transducers combine both sensing and electrical conversion within a single element (e.g., a piezoelectric crystal which generates voltage directly from mechanical force).
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.5(b) Explain the block diagram of a transducer system. How does a strain gauge differ from an LVDT?
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/transducer_block_solved.png" alt="Block Diagram of Transducer System" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>

          <p><strong>1. Transducer System Block Diagram:</strong></p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <li><strong>Sensing Element (Primary Transducer):</strong> This is the first component that interacts directly with the physical quantity being measured (measurand) and converts it into a more measurable mechanical form (like a displacement or strain).</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 4px;"><strong>Transduction Element (Secondary Transducer):</strong> This takes the intermediate mechanical output from the sensing element and converts it into a proportional electrical signal (voltage or current) which can be processed by instruments.</li>
          </ul>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>2. Difference between Strain Gauge and LVDT:</strong></p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <li><strong>Strain Gauge:</strong> It is a <em>passive</em>, <em>resistive</em> transducer. It measures extremely minute mechanical deformations (strain) on a surface by changing its electrical resistance when stretched or compressed. It requires a DC bridge circuit to measure the resistance change.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>LVDT:</strong> It is a <em>passive</em>, <em>inductive</em> transducer. It measures relatively larger linear physical displacements by moving a magnetic core inside coils. It requires an AC excitation voltage and works on the principle of mutual induction to produce a differential AC output voltage.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">3. Classification of Transducers</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body">
      <div class="sub-section-title">3.1 Based on the Stage of Energy Conversion</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Type</th>
              <th>Operational Function</th>
              <th>Practical Example</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Primary Transducer</strong></td>
              <td>Converts the physical measurand into a mechanical or intermediate form.</td>
              <td>Bourdon Tube (converts pressure into mechanical deflection).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Secondary Transducer</strong></td>
              <td>Converts the intermediate mechanical form into a proportional electrical signal.</td>
              <td>LVDT (converts core displacement into differential output voltage).</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="prose" style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Note: Most physical measurement systems connect these two in series (e.g., Pressure &rarr; Bourdon Tube &rarr; LVDT &rarr; Electrical Voltage).</em></p>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.3 (OR) Differentiate between primary and secondary transducers with suitable examples.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <table class="cmp" style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Basis of Difference</th>
                <th>Primary Transducer</th>
                <th>Secondary Transducer</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>1. Definition</strong></td>
                <td>It is the first element that senses the physical measurand and converts it into an intermediate form (usually mechanical).</td>
                <td>It is the second element that takes the intermediate mechanical output and converts it into a proportional electrical signal.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>2. Placement</strong></td>
                <td>Placed directly in contact with the physical process/medium being measured.</td>
                <td>Placed after the primary transducer in the measurement chain.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>3. Output Nature</strong></td>
                <td>Output is generally a physical displacement, pressure change, or mechanical strain.</td>
                <td>Output is strictly an electrical parameter (voltage, current, resistance).</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>4. Example</strong></td>
                <td><strong>Bourdon Tube:</strong> Senses pressure and converts it into the mechanical displacement of its tip.</td>
                <td><strong>LVDT:</strong> Senses the displacement of the Bourdon tube tip and converts it into an AC voltage.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">3.2 Based on Power / Excitation Requirements</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Type</th>
              <th>Power &amp; Working Principle</th>
              <th>Practical Examples</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Active Transducer</strong></td>
              <td><strong>Generates its own electrical output</strong>. Does not require any external electrical power supply to function (self-generating). Draws energy directly from the input quantity.</td>
              <td>Thermocouple, Piezoelectric crystal, Photovoltaic cell.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Passive Transducer</strong></td>
              <td><strong>Changes its electrical property</strong> (resistance, inductance, or capacitance). Requires an external electrical power supply (excitation source) to obtain output.</td>
              <td>LVDT, Thermistor, Strain gauge, Resistance Temperature Detector (RTD), Capacitive sensor.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box" style="margin-top: 12px;">
        <div class="green-box-title">Memory Hack for Exams</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Active = Self-Powered:</strong> Think of it as an electrical generator or a battery. It creates an EMF (voltage) directly from the measurand.</li>
          <li><strong>Passive = Externally Powered:</strong> Think of it as a resistor, inductor, or capacitor. You must pass a current or supply a voltage through it to measure the change in its parameters.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">3.3 Other Classification Criteria (Section A Quick Recall)</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Classification Basis</th>
              <th>Types &amp; Short Explanations</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Output Signal Type</strong></td>
              <td>
                • <strong>Analog:</strong> Continuous output signal (e.g., LVDT, Thermocouple).<br>
                • <strong>Digital:</strong> Discrete pulse output signal (e.g., Shaft Encoder).
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Measurand Parameter</strong></td>
              <td>Temperature, Displacement, Pressure, Velocity, Force, Flow, Humidity, etc.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Transduction Principle</strong></td>
              <td>Resistive, Inductive, Capacitive, Piezoelectric, Photoelectric, Optoelectronic.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">4. Characteristics of a Good Transducer</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>For accurate, reliable, and noise-free physical measurements, a transducer must satisfy the following critical criteria:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>High Sensitivity:</strong> It must produce a significant, easily measurable electrical output for very small changes in the physical measurand.</li>
        <li><strong>Linearity:</strong> The electrical output should vary linearly with the input quantity over its entire operating range. Nonlinearity introduces scale errors.</li>
        <li><strong>High Accuracy &amp; Repeatability:</strong> The transducer must provide identical output values when subjected to the same input under the same environmental conditions.</li>
        <li><strong>Fast Response (Dynamic Speed):</strong> The electrical output must track changes in the physical measurand rapidly and with minimal time lag.</li>
        <li><strong>No Loading Effect:</strong> The transducer must have high input impedance (or draw negligible energy) so it does not alter or load the physical quantity being measured.</li>
        <li><strong>Ruggedness:</strong> It must be robust enough to withstand mechanical shocks, overloads, and operate reliably in hostile environments.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">📐</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Module 5 — LVDT Construction, Working &amp; Measurement Instruments</strong><br>
      Learn about LVDT linear displacement measurement, its working principle, output characteristics, active vs passive comparison, and DMM operations.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">1. Linear Variable Differential Transformer (LVDT)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 Tier 1</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>The <strong>Linear Variable Differential Transformer (LVDT)</strong> is the most common electromagnetic transducer used to convert linear displacement into a proportional AC voltage signal. It is a <strong>passive, inductive</strong> secondary transducer.</p>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Constructional Details</div>
      <p>An LVDT assembly consists of the following key mechanical and electrical parts:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Primary Winding (P):</strong> Wound at the center of the former, energized by an AC excitation supply voltage. This coil generates a varying magnetic flux.</li>
        <li><strong>Two Secondary Windings (S₁ and S₂):</strong> Wound symmetrically on either side of the primary winding. They have an equal number of turns and are connected in <strong>series opposition</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>Sliding Soft Iron Core:</strong> A highly permeable ferromagnetic cylinder that slides axially inside the hollow coil former. It provides a low-reluctance magnetic path to couple flux from the primary to the secondary windings.</li>
        <li><strong>Cylindrical Former:</strong> A non-magnetic, non-conductive hollow tube that holds the coils.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — LVDT Construction Layout</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/lvdt_construction.png" alt="LVDT Construction Layout Diagram">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Draw a central Primary coil connected to an AC source and two symmetrical Secondary coils connected in series opposition. Show the ferromagnetic core running through their axes, mounted on a displacement shaft.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=linear+variable+differential+transformer+working+construction+diagram&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: LVDT Construction Diagram</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Working Principle</div>
      <p>The primary coil is excited with an AC voltage source. This creates a time-varying magnetic field that links with both secondary coils. Consequently, voltages <span class="f">E_1</span> and <span class="f">E_2</span> are induced in <span class="f">S_1</span> and <span class="f">S_2</span> respectively.</p>
      <p>Because the secondaries are connected in series opposition, the net differential output voltage is:</p>
      <p style="text-align: center; margin: 12px 0;"><span class="f" style="font-size: 1.15rem; background: #27272a; padding: 6px 12px; border-radius: 4px;">E_out = E_1 - E_2</span></p>

      <p>The position of the sliding core determines the coupling and output voltage:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Case 1: Core at Null Position (Center)</strong><br>
          The core is positioned symmetrically between <span class="f">S_1</span> and <span class="f">S_2</span>. The flux linkage is identical for both coils.<br>
          &bull; Inductions: <span class="f">E_1 = E_2</span><br>
          &bull; Net Output: <span class="f">E_out = 0 V</span><br>
          This is the zero-reference null position.
        </li>
        <li style="margin-top: 8px;">
          <strong>Case 2: Core Moved Toward S₁ (Positive Displacement, +x)</strong><br>
          The core slides to the left. S₁ links with more flux than S₂.<br>
          &bull; Inductions: <span class="f">E_1 &gt; E_2</span><br>
          &bull; Net Output: <span class="f">E_out</span> is a positive voltage.<br>
          &bull; Phase Relation: Output is exactly **in-phase** with the primary excitation voltage.
        </li>
        <li style="margin-top: 8px;">
          <strong>Case 3: Core Moved Toward S₂ (Negative Displacement, -x)</strong><br>
          The core slides to the right. S₂ links with more flux than S₁.<br>
          &bull; Inductions: <span class="f">E_2 &gt; E_1</span><br>
          &bull; Net Output: <span class="f">E_out</span> is a negative voltage (meaning phase-reversed).<br>
          &bull; Phase Relation: Output is exactly **180° out-of-phase** with the primary excitation voltage.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION B</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.3 Explain the working principle of LVDT and how it is used to measure displacement.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/lvdt_displacement_solved.png" alt="Working of LVDT for Displacement Measurement" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>

          <p><strong>Working Principle:</strong></p>
          <p>LVDT works on the principle of <strong>mutual induction</strong>. An AC excitation voltage is applied to the primary winding, creating an alternating magnetic field. This field links with the two secondary windings (<span class="f">S_1</span> and <span class="f">S_2</span>), inducing voltages <span class="f">E_1</span> and <span class="f">E_2</span>. Because the secondaries are connected in series opposition, the net output voltage is the difference: <span class="f">E_out = E_1 - E_2</span>.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Measuring Displacement (The 3 Cases):</strong></p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 8px;">
            <li><strong>Null Position (Displacement = 0):</strong> The core is perfectly centered. Flux linking <span class="f">S_1</span> equals flux linking <span class="f">S_2</span>. Therefore, <span class="f">E_1 = E_2</span>, resulting in a net output of <strong>0V</strong>.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>Positive Displacement (+x):</strong> The core moves towards <span class="f">S_1</span>. Flux linking <span class="f">S_1</span> increases, so <span class="f">E_1 &gt; E_2</span>. The output <span class="f">E_out</span> is positive and <strong>in-phase</strong> with the primary voltage.</li>
            <li style="margin-top: 6px;"><strong>Negative Displacement (-x):</strong> The core moves towards <span class="f">S_2</span>. Flux linking <span class="f">S_2</span> increases, so <span class="f">E_2 &gt; E_1</span>. The output <span class="f">E_out</span> is negative and <strong>180° out-of-phase</strong> with the primary voltage.</li>
          </ul>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>
          <p>The <strong>magnitude</strong> of the output voltage indicates the distance the core has moved, while the <strong>phase</strong> indicates the direction of displacement.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Output Characteristic Curve</div>
      <p>The relationship between the core displacement and output voltage is shown below. A phase-sensitive detector makes the output sign negative for negative displacement.</p>

      <div class="must-diag diag-box">
        <div class="dlabel">⚠️ MUST DRAW — LVDT Characteristic Curve</div>
        <div class="diag-container">
          <img class="diagram-img" src="images/lvdt_characteristic.png" alt="LVDT Characteristic Curve Graph">
        </div>
        <div class="ddesc">Plot Output Voltage against Core Displacement. Draw a straight linear line passing through (0,0). Label Null Point, Linear Region, In-Phase (positive displacement) and Out-of-Phase (negative displacement). Show non-linear bending at both extremes.</div>
        <a class="diag-btn" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=lvdt+characteristic+curve+graph&tbm=isch" target="_blank">🔍 Search: LVDT Characteristic Graph</a>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION A</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">1 Mark</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.1(d) Draw the characteristic curve of an LVDT.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; margin: 16px 0;">
            <img class="diagram-img" src="images/lvdt_characteristic_solved.png" alt="LVDT Output Characteristic Curve" style="max-width: 100%; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px;">
          </div>
          <p>The curve shows a highly linear region passing through the Null Point (0V at 0 displacement). Positive displacement (+x) yields an in-phase output, while negative displacement (-x) yields a 180° out-of-phase output. The curve bends and becomes non-linear at the extreme ends of core travel.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Determining Core Direction &amp; Magnitude</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Magnitude (How far?):</strong> The amplitude (RMS value) of the output voltage is directly proportional to the distance of core travel.</li>
          <li><strong>Direction (Which way?):</strong> The phase shift of the output relative to the primary supply (0° or 180°) reveals which side the core has moved towards.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- MST Solved Question Block -->
      <div class="qa-block" style="border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0; background: #181817;">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px;">
          <span class="badge badge-t1">🔴 MST2</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t3">SECTION C</span>
          <span class="badge badge-t2">5 Marks</span>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-q" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Q.5(d) Explain how an LVDT measures both the magnitude and direction of displacement.
        </div>
        <div class="qa-a green-box" style="margin: 0; padding: 14px;">
          <div class="green-box-title" style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent-green); margin-bottom: 8px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">Expected Answer</div>
          <p>An LVDT uses a primary coil and two identical secondary coils (<span class="f">S_1</span>, <span class="f">S_2</span>) connected in series opposition. The output is <span class="f">E_out = E_1 - E_2</span>.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Measuring Magnitude:</strong></p>
          <p>The magnitude (amount) of displacement is determined by the <strong>amplitude</strong> (RMS voltage value) of the output signal <span class="f">E_out</span>. The further the core moves from the central null position, the greater the flux linkage with one coil over the other, causing a proportionally higher differential output voltage.</p>

          <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Measuring Direction:</strong></p>
          <p>The direction of displacement is determined by the <strong>phase angle</strong> of the output signal relative to the primary excitation voltage. If the core moves towards <span class="f">S_1</span> (positive displacement), <span class="f">E_1 &gt; E_2</span>, and the output is <strong>in-phase</strong> (0° shift) with the primary. If it moves towards <span class="f">S_2</span> (negative displacement), <span class="f">E_2 &gt; E_1</span>, and the output is <strong>out-of-phase</strong> (180° shift) with the primary. A phase-sensitive demodulator circuit is used to read this phase shift and determine direction.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Advantages and Disadvantages</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Key Advantages of LVDT</th>
              <th>Key Disadvantages / Limitations</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>No Friction/Wear:</strong> The core slides freely inside the former without touching the coils, ensuring an infinite mechanical life.</td>
              <td><strong>Requires AC Excitation:</strong> Demands a stable, frequency-controlled AC supply to power the primary coil.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>High Resolution:</strong> Capable of detecting sub-microscopic displacements (has infinite theoretical resolution).</td>
              <td><strong>Needs Signal Conditioning:</strong> Requires phase-sensitive detectors and filters to convert the AC output into a DC voltage.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Linearity:</strong> Exceptional linear range (up to &plusmn;250 mm or more).</td>
              <td><strong>Temperature Sensitivity:</strong> Changes in coil resistance due to temperature affect accuracy.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Rugged &amp; Reliable:</strong> Heavy industrial shock-proof construction.</td>
              <td><strong>Stray Magnetic Fields:</strong> Prone to errors from external electromagnetic interference (requires magnetic shielding).</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Applications</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Direct Displacement Measurement:</strong> Used in machine tools, tensile testers, and valve position monitoring.</li>
        <li><strong>Indirect Measurement:</strong> Acting as a secondary transducer combined with a Bourdon tube (for pressure), proving ring (for force/load), or diaphragm.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">2. Active vs. Passive Transducers (Comparison Summary)</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body">
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Feature</th>
              <th>Active Transducers</th>
              <th>Passive Transducers</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Power Supply</strong></td>
              <td>Self-generating. Do not require external power source.</td>
              <td>Requires external excitation source to produce output.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Operating Principle</strong></td>
              <td>Generates output in the form of voltage or current.</td>
              <td>Changes electrical property (Resistance, Inductance, Capacitance).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Energy Drawing</strong></td>
              <td>Draws energy directly from the input measurand parameter.</td>
              <td>Draws power from the external excitation source.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Design Complexity</strong></td>
              <td>Simpler, but usually needs loading-effect compensations.</td>
              <td>Requires additional signal conditioning (e.g. Wheatstone bridge).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Examples</strong></td>
              <td>Thermocouple, Piezoelectric crystal, Photovoltaic cell.</td>
              <td>LVDT, Strain gauge, Thermistor, Capacitive sensor.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">3. Digital Multimeter (DMM) Overview</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t3">🔵 Tier 3</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <p>A <strong>Digital Multimeter (DMM)</strong> is an electronic instrument that measures voltage, current, and resistance, displaying the values as digital readings on an LCD screen to eliminate reading errors.</p>
      
      <div class="sub-section-title">Functional Block Diagram</div>
      <div class="block-diag-container">
        <div class="b-box blue-b">
          <div class="b-title">Analog Input</div>
          <div class="b-desc">(V, I, R probe)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="b-arrow">&rarr;</div>
        <div class="b-box purple-b">
          <div class="b-title">Attenuator / Amp</div>
          <div class="b-desc">Signal Scaling</div>
        </div>
        <div class="b-arrow">&rarr;</div>
        <div class="b-box orange-b">
          <div class="b-title">ADC</div>
          <div class="b-desc">Analog-to-Digital</div>
        </div>
        <div class="b-arrow">&rarr;</div>
        <div class="b-box green-b-box">
          <div class="b-title">LCD Display</div>
          <div class="b-desc">Direct Digital Readout</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="sub-section-title">Measurement Methodology</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Voltage Measurement:</strong> The input voltage is scaled down via a resistor network (attenuator) or amplified, and fed to the high-accuracy ADC.</li>
        <li><strong>Current Measurement:</strong> The current is passed through an internal low-resistance **shunt resistor**. The resulting voltage drop across the shunt is measured (<span class="f">V = I &times; R_shunt</span>) and converted to current.</li>
        <li><strong>Resistance Measurement:</strong> The DMM applies a constant internal reference current through the unknown resistor and measures the resulting voltage drop (<span class="f">R = V / I_ref</span>).</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="green-box">
        <div class="green-box-title">Why DMM is Superior to Analog Meters</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No Parallax Error:</strong> Direct numerical LCD display eliminates pointer visual interpretation errors.</li>
          <li><strong>Very High Input Impedance:</strong> Prevents loading effects when measuring voltage (does not alter circuit voltages).</li>
          <li><strong>Auto-Ranging:</strong> Modern DMMs automatically select the optimal range limit.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header">
      <span class="topic-title">4. Quick Revision Summary</span>
      <span class="badge badge-t2">🔵 Tier 2</span>
    </div>
    <div class="topic-body">
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Topic</th>
              <th>Core Exam Facts</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Transducer Definition</strong></td>
              <td>Converts non-electrical quantity (measurand) to proportional electrical signal.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Primary vs Secondary</strong></td>
              <td>Primary: Measurand &rarr; intermediate form (Bourdon). Secondary: Intermediate &rarr; electrical (LVDT).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Active vs Passive</strong></td>
              <td>Active: Self-powered EMF (Thermocouple). Passive: Needs external excitation (LVDT).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>LVDT Form &amp; Type</strong></td>
              <td>Linear Variable Differential Transformer. Inductive passive transducer.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>LVDT Null Position</strong></td>
              <td>Core centered &rarr; <span class="f">E_1 = E_2</span> &rarr; output <span class="f">E_out = 0 V</span>.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>LVDT Phase Behavior</strong></td>
              <td>In-phase (0°) for S1 displacement; phase-reversed (180°) for S2 displacement.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>LVDT Key Benefit</strong></td>
              <td>Contactless design means zero friction, zero wear, infinite mechanical life.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

