<!-- ==================== TAB: EXAMTIPS ==================== -->
<div id="examtips" class="panel">
  <div class="sec-intro">
    <span class="icon">⚠️</span>
    <div>
      <strong>Common Exam Mistakes to Avoid &amp; Priority Summaries</strong><br>
      Review these points before heading into the exam hall to avoid silly errors.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 1 — DC Exam Pitfalls</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mesh Loop Directions:</strong> Keep all loop current directions clockwise to make writing the KVL signs straightforward.</li>
        <li><strong>Deactivating Sources:</strong> Never trace a resistor's R_th without replacing voltage sources with short circuits and current sources with open circuits.</li>
        <li><strong>Superposition Power Trap:</strong> Do not add step-wise power quantities. Superpose current/voltage values first, then calculate power.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 2 — AC Exam Pitfalls</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Adding Series Voltages:</strong> Do not add V_R and V_L directly (<span class="f">V &ne; V_R + V_L</span>). Always use phasor vector addition.</li>
        <li><strong>Phasor Quadrants:</strong> Ensure V_C is drawn vertically downwards (lagging current) and V_L is drawn vertically upwards (leading current).</li>
        <li><strong>Reactance Trends:</strong> Remember that X_L increases with frequency (blocks high-freq), while X_C decreases with frequency (passes high-freq).</li>
        <li><strong>Confusing Units:</strong> Real power is Watts (W), reactive is VAR, and apparent is VA. Don't mix up units.</li>
        <li><strong>Power Factor Direction:</strong> State whether the power factor is "lagging" (inductive) or "leading" (capacitive). Do not just write a bare decimal.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 3 — Machines Exam Pitfalls</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Transformer DC Failure:</strong> Always explain in terms of Faraday's Law: no change in flux = no induced EMF. Add that primary behaves like a pure low resistance and can burn out under DC.</li>
        <li><strong>Pole Count vs Pole Pairs:</strong> In <span class="f">N_s = 120f/P</span>, <span class="f">P</span> is the total number of poles. If the question says "2 pole pairs", then <span class="f">P = 4</span>.</li>
        <li><strong>Torque-Slip Curve labels:</strong> You will lose points if you don't label the X-axis with both Slip (<span class="f">s = 1</span> to <span class="f">s = 0</span>) and speed, and clearly mark the stable vs unstable zones.</li>
        <li><strong>DC Motor Commutator:</strong> Armature coils carry AC internally; the commutator and carbon brushes rectifies it to DC externally. Show this component clearly in construction questions.</li>
        <li><strong>Slip Limit:</strong> Remember that slip can never be zero under load. If <span class="f">N = N_s</span>, relative motion is zero, torque drops to zero, and the rotor slows down.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 4 — Electrical Installations Exam Pitfalls</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Confusing MCB and ELCB Protection:</strong> Never write that MCB protects against shock, or that ELCB protects against short circuits. MCB protects wires/equipment from overcurrent; ELCB protects human lives from leakage currents (shocks).</li>
        <li><strong>Earthing Dimensions:</strong> Do not guess the dimensions. In Pipe Earthing, the GI pipe must be at least **38 mm diameter** and buried vertically **2.5 m deep**. Alternating charcoal and salt layers must be **15 cm thick**.</li>
        <li><strong>Charcoal vs Salt Purposes:</strong> Do not swap their functions. Charcoal **retains moisture**; salt **provides ionic conductivity** to lower the earth's resistance.</li>
        <li><strong>ELCB Trip Thresholds:</strong> Remember ELCB's standard tripping safety limits: leakage current of **30 mA** and response time of **30 ms**.</li>
        <li><strong>Steel Wire Armoured (SWA) Earthing:</strong> Always state that the outer steel wire armour must be grounded at the distribution panel so that physical cuts to the cable instantly trip the upstream breaker.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Module 5 — Transducers Exam Pitfalls</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body prose">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Confusing Active and Passive Power Supply:</strong> Remember that passive transducers *require* external excitation (like LVDT's AC source). Do not write that active transducers need power or that passive transducers generate voltage.</li>
        <li><strong>LVDT Phase Reversal:</strong> S2 displacement results in a negative voltage output *because* it is 180° out of phase. Always mention this phase shift to secure full marks.</li>
        <li><strong>LVDT Core Alignment:</strong> If the core slides completely out of the former, the coupling falls to zero. Explain that the linear range is limited by the physical overlap of core and coils.</li>
        <li><strong>DMM Current Shunt:</strong> When explaining DMM current measurement, you must explicitly state that current is measured *indirectly* by measuring the voltage drop across a known low-resistance parallel shunt.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic">
    <div class="topic-header"><span class="topic-title">Exam Priority Reference Index</span></div>
    <div class="topic-body">
      <div class="scroll-hint">Swipe horizontally &rarr;</div>
      <div class="cmp-container">
        <table class="cmp">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Topic</th>
              <th>Expected Marks</th>
              <th>Required Output in Answer</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>KCL &amp; KVL Laws</strong></td>
              <td>10 Marks</td>
              <td>Full statements, mesh diagrams, equations setup</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Superposition Theorem</strong></td>
              <td>10 Marks</td>
              <td>Separate step circuits drawing, algebraic summation</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Thevenin Equivalent</strong></td>
              <td>5 - 10 Marks</td>
              <td>Vth and Rth equations, final circuit drawing</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>RL / RC Circuits</strong></td>
              <td>5 Marks</td>
              <td>Impedance values, phasor diagram, phase angle</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Power Triangle</strong></td>
              <td>10 Marks (Sub)</td>
              <td>Labeled triangle, units, PF factor calculation</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>RMS / Average Value</strong></td>
              <td>2 - 5 Marks</td>
              <td>Derivations, peak-factor ratios</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Transformer Construction &amp; DC Fail</strong></td>
              <td>2 - 5 Marks</td>
              <td>Core/windings labels, DC fail proof, turns ratio</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Induction Motor Working &amp; Torque-Slip Curve</strong></td>
              <td>5 - 10 Marks</td>
              <td>RMF concept, slip formula, labeled curve zones</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>DC Motor Construction &amp; Working</strong></td>
              <td>5 Marks</td>
              <td>8 main components, Fleming's Left-Hand rule</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MCB Construction &amp; Working</strong></td>
              <td>5 - 10 Marks</td>
              <td>Solenoid (short circuit) and Bimetallic (overload) mechanisms, arc chute, 3 states table, internal diagram</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>ELCB Working &amp; CBCT</strong></td>
              <td>10 Marks</td>
              <td>Toroidal core diagram, normal (<span class="f">I_L = I_N</span>) vs fault (<span class="f">I_L &gt; I_N</span>) conditions, 30 mA and 30 ms trip limits</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Pipe Earthing Pit Installation</strong></td>
              <td>10 Marks</td>
              <td>Detailed pit cross section, GI pipe (38mm dia, 2.5m length), 15cm salt/charcoal, inspection chamber, funnel/mesh</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Wires and Cables</strong></td>
              <td>1 - 5 Marks</td>
              <td>Wire vs cable definition, PVC (70°C) vs XLPE (90°C), SWA mechanical protection, copper vs aluminium</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>LVDT Construction &amp; Working</strong></td>
              <td>10 Marks</td>
              <td>Former cylinder, P and S1/S2 opposite coils connected in series opposition, soft iron sliding core, AC supply, Null/S1/S2 positions</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>LVDT Characteristic Curve</strong></td>
              <td>5 - 10 Marks</td>
              <td>Core displacement vs output voltage, null point (E_out = 0V), linear operating region, phase-reversed out-of-phase region</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Transducers Classification</strong></td>
              <td>5 Marks</td>
              <td>Primary vs secondary (Bourdon tube &amp; LVDT), active vs passive (thermocouple vs LVDT), basic block diagram</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Digital Multimeter (DMM)</strong></td>
              <td>2 - 5 Marks</td>
              <td>Scaling attenuator, ADC block, LCD screen, current shunt drop V = I * R, impedance loading benefits</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
function show(id, el) {
  // Hide all panels
  document.querySelectorAll('.panel').forEach(p => p.classList.remove('active'));
  // Deactivate all tabs
  document.querySelectorAll('.tab').forEach(t => t.classList.remove('active'));
  
  // Show selected panel
  document.getElementById(id).classList.add('active');
  // Activate selected tab button
  el.classList.add('active');
  
  // Smooth scroll window back to top
  window.scrollTo({top: 0, behavior: 'smooth'});
}
</script>
</body>
</html>
